<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 19 日星期三 01:06:34 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[What’s the Matter With Barbie?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>格蕾塔·葛韦格饰演的<em>芭比娃娃</em>是一部迷人的大片冒险片，讲述了作为一个女人在社会中生存的磨难。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/8SaJ0mFhtOLswlesxFB3W53cibs=/0x0:3732x2099/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rev_1_BAR_TT2_006_High_Res_JPEG_1/original.jpg" alt="《芭比娃娃》中的芭比和肯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟</figcaption></figure>芭比乐园是一个乌托邦式的粉色天堂，里面有每一个芭比娃娃的真人大小版本，这里的生活是一场漫长的派对。芭比娃娃（玛格特·罗比饰演）每天早上在她梦想中的房子里醒来，整天和其他芭比娃娃以及许多仰慕的肯斯一起在海滩上玩耍，然后举办一个女孩之夜，这是一个精心设计的长舞蹈序列。这是一种充满欢乐的生活，是一个由品牌管理的世界，不允许任何事情出错，芭比完美的拱形高跟鞋也不允许接触地板。这就是当她在跳舞时大声问“你们想过死吗？”时特别有趣的地方。记录划痕。<br><br>格蕾塔·葛韦格 (Greta Gerwig) 饰演的<em>芭比娃娃</em>的行动就此开始，这是一场轰动一时的冒险，她烘烤了一个美泰品牌的大蛋糕，并试图把它吃掉，嘲笑美国最著名的娃娃的政治局限性，同时也给她带来了一段可信的英雄之旅。将元幽默与大量激励性真诚相结合并不是一件容易的事，但<em>芭比娃娃</em>是一个非常迷人的成功，对于一个塑料偶像来说，这是一次自我完善的冒险之旅，其存在的理由是永远不会改变，永远是同样完美的理想。与葛韦格的前两部电影一样——大获成功的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-review/544721/"><em>《伯德小姐</em></a>》和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/little-women-review-saiorse-ronan-florence-pugh/604114/"><em>《小妇人》</em></a> ——这部电影巧妙地思考了一个噩梦般的难题：仅仅试图以女性的身份存在于社会中，只是穿着更多的日光服装。<br><br>最初，<em>芭比娃娃</em>似乎会遵循其他有关品牌的电影设定的公式，例如<em>《乐高大电影》</em>和<em>《刺猬索尼克》</em> ，其中来自品牌世界的角色跨越某些维度障碍进入我们的世界，犯错误，并试图计算与令人沮丧的现实世俗。罗比的芭比娃娃（她的全名是刻板芭比娃娃，以区别于从事医生或总统等工作的芭比娃娃）被迫通过一系列戏剧性事件与她的存在焦虑作斗争，她的任务是探寻现实世界弄清楚她出了什么问题。<br><br>芭比最喜欢的肯（瑞恩·高斯林饰）尾随其后，部分是为了支持，部分是因为他生活中唯一的作用就是靠近她。虽然芭比是《芭比乐园》围绕的对象，但肯显然缺乏目标，反复强调他的工作被简单地指定为“海滩”——不是救生员，甚至不是游泳运动员。他只是海滩肯，永远穿着短裤站在沙滩上，脸上挂着笑容。高斯林的表演滑稽地揭示了这个漫无目的的动作人物浅薄但强烈的痛苦，这是一种有血有肉的<em>玩具</em>总动员心理剧（尽管芭比确实明确表示，她和她所有的朋友在他们的生殖器处只有毫无特征的肿块）。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">阅读：芭比真的能拥有这一切吗？</a><br><br>如果您对芭比乐园的规则以及它如何与我们的现实共存有任何疑问，请放弃。葛韦格与她的搭档兼经常合作者诺亚·鲍姆巴赫 (Noah Baumbach) 共同创作了这部电影，她并不太在意宇宙间的运输规则——只要知道芭比和肯在不同环境之间轻松跳跃是可行的。更重要的是，面对我们的世界，芭比必须面对双重恐惧：认识到女性的生活并不是美泰产品所宣传的修剪整齐、无所不能的梦想，而且现实世界中的许多女性事实上，她怨恨她代表了一个不可能的标准。<br><br>这种自我指涉的策略很容易落空：自 1959 年推出以来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">芭比娃娃作为女权主义象征的局限性</a>就一直受到广泛讨论。美泰对这部电影的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/07/10/after-barbie-mattel-is-raiding-its-entire-toybox">深入参与</a>也似乎是一个创意陷阱，“对于葛韦格来说，无论她多么努力地向观众眨眼，她都很难克服这一点。但是，通过将芭比娃娃放在我们阴郁的星球上并迫使她考虑自己的目的，葛韦格确实以某种方式挖掘出了一些真正的深度。把刻板的芭比从芭比乐园中移走，然后把她扔到洛杉矶，她只是另一个在这个对她的存在本质上充满敌意的世界中努力寻找意义的女人。她现实生活中的化身是格洛丽亚（亚莉卡·费雷拉饰演的可爱角色），一位美泰公司的员工，对 21 世纪的女性气质也充满了类似的怀疑。<br><br>与此同时，肯遇到了一个肯定和支持他的世界（或者至少是他所占据的强壮的男性身体），这让他充满了放射性的赋权感。这就是<em>芭比</em>的元智慧实际上与真实情节的交叉点：葛韦格聪明地意识到，现实生活中的芭比只会面临怀疑和批评，而肯则是一个终极空容器，等待着被废话填满。但<em>芭比</em>从来没有陷入一场廉价的男女生最终对决；它只是考虑了向我们这些疲惫而自愿的消费者出售自我形象的不同方式，即使世界变得更加精明和愤世嫉俗。它通过明亮的音乐数字、尖刻的俏皮话和正确的感伤主义来做到这一点，更令人印象深刻。<em>芭比</em>知道，但它的眼中仍然闪烁着乐观的光芒，担心主角可能会超越其他人对她的预测。毕竟，没有什么危机是一场好的舞会解决不了的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 23:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/</item><item><title><![CDATA[How Hollywood’s Businessmen Got It So Wrong]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与 Xochitl Gonzalez 对话，了解谁真正打破了娱乐业<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/q7mt7K_3OOEUUjvqB4N6Z2-EQZM=/1x313:6041x3710/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1540946623-1/original.jpg" alt="作家的罢工纠察队标语列出要求与流媒体收入" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>罗宾·贝克/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>上周，SAG-AFTRA 约 16 万名成员参加了罢工，加入了自 5 月份以来一直在罢工的美国作家协会。正如我的同事 Xochitl Gonzalez <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">所说</a>，“好莱坞机器……已经正式停止运转。”我和 Xochitl 聊了聊谁真正打破了好莱坞。<br><br>首先，这是来自<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/">田纳西州是民主国家吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/">唐纳德·特朗普的“可怕消息”</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastructure/674735/">赞扬电话号码</a></li><strong>最高管理层的无知</strong><br><br>昨天，我的同事索奇特尔·冈萨雷斯（Xochitl Gonzalez）（她本人也是一名罢工编剧）在撰写有关好莱坞罢工的文章时，创造了<i>“高管无知”</i>一词来解释娱乐界正在发生的事情。 “好莱坞的首席执行官看到了 Netflix 的成功，竞相复制一种模式，但不知道这种模式是否可持续，这种模式依赖于工会人才不断生产新的（且昂贵的）娱乐内容，”她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">解释道</a>。 “他们对企业的看法是错误的，但更错误的是他们认为劳工会遵守规定。”我打电话给索奇特尔，询问娱乐业高管是如何犯下如此错误的，以及她和她的罢工同事现在是否感到充满希望。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔·法塔尔：</b>高管们在全力投入流媒体业务时犯下的重大错误是什么？<br><br> <b>Xochitl Gonzalez：</b>我记得特别是在新冠疫情期间，显然这些事情一直在进行中，但突然间每个人都在竞相推出流媒体平台。那时，我正在对我的处女作小说进行试点改编<i>。</i>我的第一个想法是，<i>这如何可持续？</i>这看起来不像是一个可行的模型，更不用说一次又一次地匹配了。<br><br>现在，高管们意识到这种模式并不能赚钱，这一点我并不否认。我认为，当你看到高管们获得如此丰厚的报酬时，很难说你会破产或破产，更搞笑的是，即使是外行人也能看出这将是一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/03/why-subscriptions-are-hard-to-cancel/623885/">难以跟上的模式</a>。现在，高管们表示，他们付不起人才的工资。但他们设计了一种利用合同的模式——本质上，这是演员和编剧一直通过剩余报酬获得报酬的一种变通办法。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔：</b>解释一下解决方法。<br><br> <b>Xochitl：</b>例如， <i>《老友记》</i>中的演员们非常富有，因为<i>《老友记》</i>在各个不同的地方都获得了许可，并且可以在有线电视和广播电视上观看。现在<i>《老友记》</i>在 Max 上播出，演员们在该平台上的收入就少了很多。过去，没有人对这样的想法有实质性的异议：如果一部剧收视率很高，编剧和演员就应该看到其中的一部分，因为它是我们创作的。这不是我们引入的新想法。我们只是试图纠正<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/mandy-moore-residuals-sag-aftra-strike-1235538930/#recipient_hashed=7b2a08444fba33a6c4d3b1925c6b91b0e7d0c6fb0d714a3d66f9b34ae571dd0d&amp;recipient_salt=e7bd5c9471e7b1b6f7c359351da66603f51296e3e4776c29585879bad446bb77">新系统</a>利用漏洞的方式。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔：</b>你对罢工有希望吗？<br><br><b>索奇特尔：</b>我愿意。 SAG 和 WGA 的很多关注点都有重叠。我认为很多人并不总是意识到这一点——对于美国演员工会来说尤其如此——但很多能够以演员或编剧谋生的人都是中产阶级。大部分人都没有赚到钱。这些问题如此关乎生存，这一事实让人们更加坚定。上次<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/11/what-reagan-did-for-hollywood/248391/">我们一起罢工</a>时，我们取得了绝对历史性的成果。所以我感到充满希望，但短期内我感到担忧。洛杉矶有一家食品银行，为美国演员工会会员提供价值超过 300 美元的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CuxXUpHSQUG/?img_index=1">免费食品杂货</a>。有些人需要这些免费的杂货；这是一个挑战。<br><br>我认为当地的人们会坚持下去，因为这不仅仅是因为你的工作而受到重视。问题在于，我们是否确保这是一个可持续发展的职业？我想这会变得血腥。它会对地面上的人造成很大的伤害。但最终，我觉得我们会赢。主要是因为，正如我在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">写WGA</a>时所说，没有我们、没有故事、没有表演，那还有什么？<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">商人打破了好莱坞。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">思考好莱坞编剧罢工的四种方式</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>前总统特朗普表示，他收到一封信， <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/special-counsel-informs-trump-target-probe-efforts-overturn/story?id=101404037">通知他</a>自己是特别检察官杰克·史密斯调查企图推翻2020年总统选举的目标，这创造了再次起诉的可能性。</li><li>一名美军士兵<a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/north-korea-us-national-american-crosses-border-demilitarized-zone-dmz-tour/">脱离</a>边境旅游团闯入朝鲜；据信他已被拘留。</li><li>根据新闻媒体获得的一封电子邮件，德克萨斯州公共安全部的医护人员<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/18/us/texas-troopers-migrant-treatment-concerns/index.html">被告知，将</a>试图穿越南部边境进入里奥格兰德河的人们赶走，并在酷热的情况下拒绝给他们供水。</li><strong>快讯</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/work-in-progress/"><b>正在进行的工作</b></a><b>：</b><b> </b><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homelessness-housing-crisis/674737/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯写道</a>，加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。它暗示了无家可归的根本原因。</li> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">在这里探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br><strong>晚读</strong><br><br>语音机器人让我无言以对<br><br><em>萨希尔·德赛</em><br><br><p>说出我的名字 Saahil Desai 并不难。 Saahil：与<i>锯木厂</i>押韵，或者至少可以让你达到 90%。 Desai：就像<i>决定</i>把最后一点砍掉。确实如此。</p><p>然而，我的名字常常会被淹没在一大堆失态和错误中。最常见的一个，Sa <i>-heel</i> ，至少是一个诚实的尝试——不像它的突变双胞胎，一个单音节的混乱，听起来像<i>海豹。</i>其他人则违背了所有可能的逻辑。有一次，一位大学同学读到我的名字，停顿了一下，然后自信地说：“嗨，西雅图。”</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">如何兑换社交媒体</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/athens-greece-wildfires-residents-flee-photos/674741/">照片：希腊雅典郊外野火肆虐。</a></li><strong>文化突破</strong><br><br><b>读。</b>小说家黛博拉·利维的最新作品<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/august-blue-deborah-levy/9780374602048?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《奥古斯特·布鲁》</i></a>继续<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/august-blue-deborah-levy-novel/674740/">其职业生涯中</a>寻找真实的自我。<br><br><b>手表。</b>伪纪录片<b> </b><i>戏剧营</i>（现已在剧院上映）是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/theater-camp-movie-review/674712/">对创造力的一首可爱的颂歌</a>，并提醒人们艺术社区的重要性。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br> <em>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-strike-2023-streaming/674748/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-strike-2023-streaming/674748/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Obsessed With the Life That Could Have Been]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在她的最新小说中，黛博拉·利维继续在她的职业生涯中寻找真实的自我。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/WlVJs3j0-mbUcpieTEIP8Zs_XAs=/0x0:6286x3536/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1218008565_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个女人的脸的一部分看起来被捕捉到一个挂坠盒中" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>遗产艺术/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">疫情初期，</span>我们见面变得更加困难。人脸，个性的终极标志，哲学家伊曼纽尔·列维纳斯（Emmanuel Levinas）称之为“第一次披露”，突然被织物包裹起来。街上遇到的陌生人更加陌生——遮住他们面容的面具成了投射焦虑想法的屏幕。<br><br>在出生于南非、现居伦敦北部的小说家黛博拉·利维 (Deborah Levy) 的最新著作<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/august-blue-deborah-levy/9780374602048?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《八月蓝色》</i></a>中，一位名叫艾尔莎·安德森 (Elsa Anderson) 的音乐会钢琴家在雅典的跳蚤市场上瞥见一名戴着蓝色医用口罩的妇女正在购买一件俗气的小玩意——一对玩具机械马。 ——她莫名其妙地也非常想要自己得到它。由于无法完全看到这个女人的脸，艾莎开始相信她实际上在这个神秘而迷人的陌生人身上看到了她自己的某个版本，或者更确切地说，是某种分身。 “当时我的一个惊人想法是，我和她是同一个人。”<br><br>如果利维<i>没有</i>以 2020 年大封锁结束后的情况为背景创作一部小说，那么她的读者会感到惊讶，当时“每个人都显得茫然和沮丧”，尽管大流行最严重的时期已经过去。她总是用近代的决定性事件——柏林墙倒塌、金融危机、英国脱欧——作为她故事的配乐。生活在历史性混乱中所带来的流离失所和不安感，赋予了她的书一种威胁的边缘，并暗示着其相对简短掩盖了雄心壮志。<br><br>列维的典型主体是知识分子、研究男性暴君的历史学家、诗人、人类学博士生。这些人物是 21 世纪的赫尔佐格，他们情不自禁地通过智力固着的棱镜来表达自己的神经症。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/hot-milk-deborah-levy/9781620406700?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《热牛奶》</i></a>中，人类学家与母亲的关系是一种不断翻转的亲缘结构。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-man-who-saw-everything-deborah-levy/9781632869852?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《洞察一切的人》</i></a>中，这位历史学家指出，斯大林会通过向女性扔面包来调情——我们了解到他暴虐的父亲也有这种扔碳水化合物的习惯。这些学术重叠是她书中的乐趣之一。<br><br>艾尔莎符合利维的原型。她是一位神童，6 岁时被养父母从养父母身边挑选出来，以便一位伟大的老师亚瑟·戈德斯坦 (Arthur Goldstein) 将她培养成一名艺术大师。他是艾尔莎笔下的同性恋、浮夸迂腐的亨利·希金斯，训练她摆脱平凡的思维，以便她能够掌握古典曲目。<br><br>但当这本书开始时，艾莎正在雅典的市场里翻找，她刚刚羞辱性地跌跌撞撞地偏离了戈德斯坦所规划的伟大之路。当她在维也纳金色大厅演奏拉赫玛尼诺夫的第二钢琴协奏曲时，她开始下意识地演奏自己的不和谐音符，她最终意识到这是她自己创作冲动的表现，然后走下舞台，而大师轻蔑地嘲笑她。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/10/deborah-levy-man-who-saw-everything-review/599677/">阅读：黛博拉·利维令人迷惑却引人入胜的小说</a><br><br>一场身份危机开始于音乐会前夕，当时艾莎将头发染成蓝色，她将这一事件描述为与抛弃她的生母断绝了关系，最终使她变得虚弱。和利维笔下的许多其他主角一样，她发现自己在欧洲旅游胜地南部的各个地方穿梭，在阳光普照的蜿蜒旅程中寻求治愈。<br><br>利维的小说有一种不可否认的、也是不可否认的、令人着迷的怪异之处。引入分身是一种典型的非典型举动。利维并不完全实践魔幻现实主义；她的书与生活的实际情况联系得太紧密，不可能这样描述。但她的情节以奇怪的时刻和滑稽的误解为基础——如果不是魔法，确切地说，那么机缘巧合似乎融入了她的虚构世界。小细节被赋予了象征意义；单词和短语的重复具有模糊的目的。<br><br>但利维的替身的存在是她小说中最明显的故意想法之一。这是她的女权主义的核心，政治承诺巧妙地渗透到她的小说中，并不太微妙地塑造了她的非小说类作品。她用它来理解自己生活中的挣扎。这个分身不仅跟踪利维的主角，而且还跟踪他。它贯穿了她的全部工作。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">在美国，</span>人们对利维的喜爱很大程度上取决于她精彩的回忆录三部曲——她称之为“活生生的自传”——其中包括一本薄薄的卷子<i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/things-i-don-t-want-to-know-on-writing-deborah-levy/9781635572247?affiliate_id=atl-347">《我不想知道的事情》</a> 。</i>这本书是对乔治·奥威尔著名文章《我为何写作》的女权主义回应。利维采纳了奥威尔所说的“写作的四大动机”，并将其用作她的章节标题，尽管她的论点的实质内容是隐晦的，而奥威尔的则不然。让奥威尔作为她的陪衬并不是一种激进的反传统姿态。相反，她利用这个模板来解释自己，表明推动女作家的冲动与感动奥威尔的冲动有多么不同。<br><br>把自己的回忆录附在奥威尔身上似乎有点鲁莽，因为这位散文家的传记是独立写作生活的浪漫定义，在顽强地追求正义事业中回避物质荣耀。但有一个相似之处并不让人感到紧张：利维在她职业生涯的大部分时间里也遭受了严重的忽视。 50 岁出头时，她无法为自己的小说<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/swimming-home-deborah-levy/9781620401699?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《游泳之家》</i></a>找到主要出版商，因此她在英国政府和读者订阅的支持下，通过一家小型非营利出版社出版了该书。<br><br> <i>《游泳回家》</i>是她 15 年来的第一部小说，这种中年成功的情况很少见。这让评论家大吃一惊，并让她连续三年入围布克奖决赛。考虑到她的自传中包含的故事——一系列的个人危机和对真实自我的长期搜救任务，利维的繁荣来得迟来并不令人意外。<br><br> 5岁时，南非警察的一个特别部门半夜从家里的平房里抓走了她的父亲，一位学者和活动家。他最终与他在非洲人国民大会上的战友纳尔逊·曼德拉一起接受审判。在她父亲入狱期间，利维的母亲将她送到德班的教母那里，在那里她在一所天主教学校上学，并生活在严厉的族长的屋顶下。<br><br>当种族隔离政府释放了她 9 岁的父亲时，全家前往英国寻求庇护，但流亡加剧了她日益增长的疏离感，因为她试图融入 20 世纪 70 年代英国沉闷的生活。利维通过将自己重塑为一个青少年波西米亚人来应对这种混乱，尽管她坐在工人阶级油腻的勺子里，没有一丝巴黎精致的感觉。 “我是一个悲伤的女孩，模仿着一个悲伤的女孩，”她回忆道。<br><br>她的疏离感一直伴随着她进入成年期——当母亲意味着她要以牺牲自己的幸福和艺术成就为代价来照顾家人：“在家里没有宾至如归的感觉是社会及其更大故事的开始。女性的不满。”<br><br>利维最终选择了分身的想法，这是对她个人的骚乱历史和挥之不去的不真实感的回应，这是可以理解的。如此频繁地偏离预期路线，不可避免地会着迷于菲利普·罗斯曾经描述的“反生活”，即存在的另一种版本，如果存在的话<i>会怎样？</i><i> </i>完全呈现在想象中。在她的回忆录中，她想象自己遇到了自己的替身——离婚后，她年轻的移民自我在中年拜访她，当时她坐在伦敦北部的公寓楼里观看<i>英国烘焙大赛</i>。<br><br>双重人格的想法切入了她女权主义的本质：母亲们被她们在孩子出生之前的生活以及她们对家庭做出的让步所困扰。解放是恢复不受社会束缚的另类自我。这是“学习如何成为一个主体，而不是一个错觉”。<br><br>利维小说的令人兴奋之处在于，它们充满了这种不懈的探索精神。抄袭奥威尔的论文格式是她顽皮的实验主义的象征。她最好的小说都带有结构性风险。 <i>《目睹一切的人》</i>分为两部分，相隔 28 年，每一部分都重复着同一个不太可能的时刻：书中的中心人物走进艾比路的人行横道，然后被一名德国男子驾驶的汽车撞倒。这是对著名形象和巧妙构思的致敬。事故的报复让她重新回顾了本书前半部分的事件。随着时间的推移，叙述者对其人际关系的自恋误读被暴露出来。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/jenny-erpenbeck-german-writer-kairos-memoir-book/673789/">阅读：在废墟中书写</a><br><br>利维的作品集就像弗洛伊德的符号和短语宇宙，这些符号和短语反复出现在她的书中以及她的书中。她描述了有人错误地引用了<i>《共产党宣言》</i>中关于幽灵出没欧洲的著名台词——然后<i>幽灵</i>这个词开始困扰小说本身，每次出现都会激怒读者，迫使读者更深入地思考它的含义。<br><br>她使用相同措辞提出的某些问题逐字出现在不同的书中。在她的一本回忆录中，她问道：“我们如何处理那些我们不想知道的事情？”这个问题启发了这本书的书名——它再次出现在<i>《八月的蓝色》中。</i>这个问题会让那些被反生活折磨的人困扰。<br><br> <i>《<span class="smallcaps">令人敬畏的蓝色》</span></i><span class="smallcaps">有其自己</span>的发明，但与利维最近的书无关。最后，艾莎坐在她的老师兼代理父亲戈德斯坦身边，看着他躺在撒丁岛的一座小房子里，垂死挣扎。他有点欺负人，但却是她生命中唯一的感情来源，无论这取决于她的艺术成功。<br><br>她确实过着戈德斯坦为她选择的生活。他把她的名字从安改为艾尔莎，并规划了她的职业生涯，部分原因是为了证明自己作为一名教师的天才。只有在他即将死亡的阴影下，艾莎才抛开恐惧和怨恨，去了解她亲生父母的身份。最后，这是我们在电影院里一遍又一遍看到的典型情节：一个被收养的孩子面对她对自我认知的可怕渴望。<br><br>更重要的是，利维对古典音乐世界的女权主义批评一反常态地崎岖不平。她过度渲染了一个女人被迫掌握男性天才的分数同时压制自己的创造力的主题。艾莎在空闲时间观看舞者伊莎多拉·邓肯 (Isadora Duncan) 的 YouTube 视频，羡慕她的艺术自由，这种全神贯注与艾莎被剧目束缚的感觉形成了一种解放性的对比，这有点过于粗暴了。<br><br>然而，即使在这部不太完全实现的小说中——她最好的作品是<i>《看见一切的男人》</i>和<i>《热牛奶</i>》——利维也展示了她独特的思想。如果说女权主义的最终目标，正如她所宣扬的那样，是要夺回个性，消除一个人更充实、更真实的自我的阴影，那么她的散文就体现了这一想法。她的语言非常优美，是她自己的：她将自杀念头的娱乐性描述为“站在禁忌的牧场上”；她称艾莎染过的鬃毛是“非常有表现力的头发”。她的图像是辛辣的原创。她在一次潜水旅行中让艾莎毫不畏惧地用叉子刺伤海胆，向我们展示了艾莎的残忍能力。<br><br>利维的研究对象都是可信的知识分子，因为她也是。当她不经意地在对话中插入一段关于尼采失败的音乐实验的即兴片段时，它是有机而有趣的。她对弗洛伊德的解读从来都隐藏在她散文的表面之下——她如此频繁地重复弗洛伊德的短语“我们不想知道的事情”，这几乎是一个弗洛伊德式的笑话。作为一名观察者，她能够回忆起刚刚过去的历史性时刻，以令人不安的精确度描述了大流行病的倦怠，捕捉到了隔离后日常人际互动的尴尬。<br><br>由于她的女权主义和她的古怪行为，利维往往会被批评家挤到一个特定的位置，而这种方式无法体现她书中的雄心壮志。英国<i>《金融时报》</i>最近称她为“邪教小说家”。但这感觉很吝啬。相反，我们应该按照她的本来面目来称呼她：当今工作中最活跃、最令人满意的思想小说家之一。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 15:43:30 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/august-blue-deborah-levy-novel/674740/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/august-blue-deborah-levy-novel/674740/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Donald Trump’s ‘Horrifying News’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位前总统表示，他预计将再次被司法部起诉，这次的指控与 1 月 6 日有关。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EXUymmeWjevA4iV9mqdMuumPbTM=/0x66:3514x2043/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1439325943/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普戴着 MAGA 帽子的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>赢得麦克纳米/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>尽管唐纳德·特朗普有时被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bostonglobe.com/2023/04/04/opinion/another-teflon-don-finally-gets-scratched-court/">特氟隆唐</a>”——这个标签不仅与他自己的名字有关，而且与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/08/trump-gravano-gotti-mafia/568273/">他的作案手法</a>有关——但事实并不是他逃脱了一切后果，而是他最令人震惊的行为。他曾<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/e-jean-carroll-verdict/674001/">在诽谤案中败诉</a>，他的公司因<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/09/ny-attorney-general-trump-organization-was-fraud/671500/">逃税</a>而受到指责，他还被指控犯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-indictment-arrignment-speech/673616/">有错综复杂的商业犯罪</a>。但他犯下的最大罪行——尤其是试图窃取 2020 年总统选举的胜利——却没有受到惩罚。<br><br>这种模式可能很快就会被打破。特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110735295720085796">今天早上发表声明</a>称，他周日晚上收到了司法部特别顾问杰克·史密斯的一封“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/archives/jm/criminal-resource-manual-160-sample-target-letter">目标信</a>”。他说史密斯给了他四天的时间向大陪审团报告，调查特朗普试图颠覆 2020 年大选和 2021 年 1 月 6 日国会大厦骚乱。此类信件通常是起诉书的前奏。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：文书工作的妙招</a><br><br>特朗普并不是最可靠的消息来源。他是个顽固的骗子，三月份错误地声称他即将在纽约的一桩案件中被捕——事实证明，他被捕了，但直到一段时间后才被捕。尽管如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/07/18/us/trump-jan-6-letter#trump-jan-6-letter">一些</a>媒体已经从其他消息<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/special-counsel-informs-trump-target-probe-efforts-overturn/story?id=101404037">来源</a>证实特朗普收到了这封信，而且这一消息与史密斯调查的已知情况相符。<br><br>如果可以合理地假设特朗普确实可能被指控犯有与 1 月 6 日相关的罪行，那么这仍然留下了很大的疑问。其中最重要的是这些可能是什么犯罪。传闻中的可能性包括<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/04/12/trump-fundraising-fraud-special-counsel/">筹款违规</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/28/us/politics/jan-6-prosecutors-trump-fund-raising.html">电汇欺诈</a>等检方惯用手段，甚至叛乱——这是一种极其罕见的指控，但众议院调查委员会 1 月 6 日将一项指控<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/january-6-committee-criminal-referral-donald-trump/672514/">提交</a>给了司法部。<br><br>史密斯可以选择对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">文件政变</a>的许多参与者提出广泛的指控，这将是一个更复杂的案件，但很可能会被定罪，或者他可以更狭隘地关注特朗普或一小部分助手，这可能是一个情况更简单，但在政治上更具煽动性。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：唐纳德·特朗普可能即将被起诉的指南</a><br><br>特朗普发现自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">在全国各地的司法管辖区陷入了法律麻烦</a>，以至于他的律师上周在要求联邦法院推迟对机密文件处理不当的审判时引用了这些麻烦。 （史密斯上个月在该案中起诉了特朗普。）在曼哈顿，这位前总统面临的指控主要是向一名自称与他发生性关系的成人电影演员支付封口费。人们普遍预计佐治亚州富尔顿县地方检察官将在 8 月的某个时候提出与 2020 年选举相关的指控。<br><br>这些案件可以沿着两个轴绘制：定罪概率和犯罪严重性。犯罪就是犯罪，但曼哈顿案相对来说是小事，一些法律观察家认为检方的法律理论值得怀疑。文件案不仅非常严重——它涉及一些对国家安全最敏感的材料——而且事实相对简单，对特朗普来说也是毁灭性的。富尔顿县案件很严重，因为它涉及颠覆选举的企图，但也仅限于佐治亚州的行动；降低定罪的可能性具有挑战性。<br><br>但与 1 月 6 日相关的潜在联邦案件可能是最重要的案件。这些罪行再严重不过了：特朗普首先通过法律和政治计划，然后更绝望地通过武力来挫败选民的意愿。从来没有哪位总统如此直接地攻击美国民主的基础。相比之下，即使是尼克松的罪行也显得黯然失色。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：特朗普为避免起诉而进行的最后一搏</a><br><br>通俗地说，特朗普显然有罪。每个人都看着他声称他赢得了一场他没有赢得的选举。他们听到他向包括佐治亚州议员布拉德·拉芬斯佩格在内的官员施压，要求为他争取选票。他们听说他在 1 月 6 日煽动骚乱。他的行为非常恶劣，以至于众议院对他进行了弹劾，大多数参议员，包括一些共和党人，投票判定有罪——尽管仍低于定罪所需的三分之二。<br><br>然而，有些事情可能用普通话来说是明显正确的，但仍然具有挑战性或无法向陪审团证明。 “你和我都知道，这不是秘密，但在法庭上，在有争议的听证会上，用可接受的证据，排除合理怀疑来证明这一点要困难得多，”前联邦检察官保罗·罗森茨威格(Paul Rosenzweig)早些时候告诉我今年。二月，特朗普发布了一份备忘录<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">，列出了他可能对与骚乱相关的任何指控进行辩护的理由</a>。在今天的声明中，他将针对他的案件描述为“选举干涉”，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/trump-calls-china-interfere-2020-election/599365/">“我是橡皮，你是胶水</a>”肆无忌惮的惊人例子。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment-unsealed/674353/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：可以想象到的最愚蠢的犯罪</a><br><br>政治敏感性也是不可避免的。无论史密斯指控什么，这都将是史无前例的。特朗普将在选举期间对这些指控提出异议。他的律师已经在寻求将文件案的审判<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-wants-use-his-campaign-escape-prosecution/674672/">推迟到 2024 年大选之后</a>，如果他获胜，他很可能能够命令司法部结案。<br><br>所有这些因素意味着没有人可以自信地预测定罪，更不用说监禁了。但与 1 月 6 日相关的目标信将是追究特朗普对美国的罪行负责的首批具体步骤之一。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 15:15:07 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Root Cause of the Homelessness Crisis]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/9xDFDUsEn1ZSw2w_-GO9zCLrUzg=/0x24:4799x2723/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1238537050/original.jpg" alt="2022 年 2 月 16 日，加利福尼亚州洛杉矶市中心附近，收容无家可归者的帐篷在关闭的店面前排成一排。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>弗雷德里克·J·布朗/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>美国 30% 的无家可归者和 50% 的无家可归者居住在加利福尼亚州，总数超过 170,000 人。无家可归<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/01/homelessness-affordable-housing-crisis-democrats-causes/672224/">主要是更广泛的住房负担能力危机的结果</a>，而这又主要是地方政府在最需要的地方建造新住房的难度的结果。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/BenBayer/status/1634194893579984900?s=20">专家</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://reason.com/podcast/2022/01/12/michael-shellenberger-how-progressives-ruined-american-cities/">政客</a>经常声称，加州无家可归危机实际上是人们为了更好的天气或更好的公共福利而离开其他州的结果。但新的研究对这一理论提出了质疑。上个月，加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。它包含来自加州 3,200 名无家可归者的调查数据以及对其中 300 多名无家可归者的深入采访。<br><br>接受调查的无家可归者绝大多数是当地人，而不是来自远方的移民：90% 的人失去了在加利福尼亚州的最后一个住房，75% 的人在他们经历无家可归的同一县失去了它。在 10% 来自其他地方的人中，30% 出生在加利福尼亚州。其他大多数人都有家庭或雇佣关系，或者以前曾在该州居住过。<br><br>退一步来说，数以万计的人在无家可归后搬到加州的想法毫无意义。搬家很贵。失去住房的人很少有办法在全国范围内运送自己、家人、宠物和财物。抛开这一点不谈，无家可归使人们变得脆弱。第一本能不是搬到新的地方，而是留在家人和朋友网络以及潜在的工作机会附近。<br><br>研究人员小心翼翼地确定受访者的来源，但没有促使他们给出任何一个答案。 “我们没有说，‘嘿，你来自加利福尼亚州吗？’”该研究的首席研究员、贝尼奥夫无家可归者和住房计划主任玛戈特·库谢尔告诉我。她说，受访者被要求回顾他们的生活史，解释导致他们无家可归的情况。在此过程中，他们被要求澄清关键的地理细节。<br><br>例如，这是她与我分享的一次交流：<br><br><p>采访者：那你当时（第一次失去住房）几岁？</p><p>回答者：我33岁了。</p><p>采访者：三十三，好吧。那是在这儿，还是在哪儿？</p><p>受访者：那实际上是在加利福尼亚州的波莫纳。</p><p>采访者：波莫纳，好的。然后你一直呆在那里吗？你无家可归之后发生了什么？你的转变是什么？</p><p>受访者：嗯，我有点跳来跳去，但在地理位置上并不是很多。我有点摇摆不定，只是因为，就像我说的，我根本不知道如何应对无家可归的情况。我以前从未无家可归过。我感觉不舒服。我正在努力寻找睡觉的地方。每次他们把你赶走时，你都会说：“好吧，我不能睡在那里，所以我就去这里吧。”所以，事情就是这样发生的。我最终来到了一个叫克莱蒙特的城市……还有另一个克莱蒙特实际上就在波莫纳附近。这就是我住的地方，在波莫纳和克莱蒙特、安大略省[奇诺]之间来回穿梭。它的地理面积不是很大，但技术上是不同的城市。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：您[无家可归]之前住在哪里？</p><p>受访者：加利福尼亚州圣贝纳迪诺。我妈妈的房子有五间卧室。她在那里住了50年零14天。</p><p>采访者：你妈妈的房子，好吧。你离开那所房子回到这里。</p><p>对方：就走开了。</p><p>记者：是因为她去世了吗？</p><p>受访者：不，因为我的家人很恶魔而且很可怕。我们应该哀悼她，而他们只是来看看能从房子里得到什么和其他东西。所以，我就离开了，因为事情不应该是这样的。我哥哥因为照顾我妈妈、殴打我等等而让我住院三次。我原谅他们；我想继续前进。无家可归只是一个停留；你给汽车充电，充电，然后重新上路。我生命中最美好的部分就是我生命的下一部分。就是这样。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到这里的？那么你在德克萨斯州；你有房子。</p><p>回答者：我有房子。我得了癌症，肾癌。我失去了工作，失去了房子……</p><p>采访者：你在休斯顿做什么——什么样的工作？</p><p>受访者：我当了20年卡车司机。</p><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到加州的呢？</p><p>受访者：我来自加利福尼亚州。于是我就回到了家。</p>加利福尼亚州是大多数无家可归者的<em>家园</em>。最常报告的失去住房的原因是由于失业或工作时间减少而导致收入减少。其次是经济原因，其次是两个社会原因：居民之间的冲突，以及对室友或家庭成员施加压力的担忧。在一个更负担得起的环境中，这些社会原因只会导致地址的改变，而不是无家可归。<br><br>通过提前识别高危人群来防止无家可归是非常困难的。部分原因是，处于不稳定局势中的人们比真正失去家园的人们要大得多，而且正如报告所揭示的那样，当人们确实失去家园时，这种情况发生得非常快。签订租约的受访者平均提前 10 天收到他们将失去住房的通知。 60% 没有租约的人报告中位数只有一天。这并不是联系社会服务机构寻求帮助的宽限期。<br><br>然而库舍尔强调，一些无家可归的现象是可以预见的。许多人因监狱或看守所而变得无家可归——占受访者的 19%。更重要的是，67% 的受访者入狱时无家可归。然而，只有不到 20% 的人表示在退出时获得了福利、医疗保健或住房支持。库舍尔表示，阻止加州新一轮无家可归者的流动是“轻而易举的事”：“我们知道人们在哪里；我们知道他们会发生什么。”<br><br>一旦人们失去了家园，搬进新家就变得极具挑战性。受访者表示，距离上次拥有住房的时间中位数为 22 个月。近 90% 的受访者表示，住房成本影响了他们摆脱无家可归的能力。一位受访者表示：“我曾尝试自己寻找公寓，但我想确保自己能买得起。而他们中的大多数人，他们想要三倍的租金。仅就单间公寓或一间卧室而言，价格为 1,100 美元、1,200 美元，仅此而已。我说，‘哇’，你知道吗？这意味着我必须赚到 3,300 美元。我并没有这么做。而且我不会很快做到这一点。”<br><br>超过一半的受访者表示，他们<em>能</em>负担得起的住房距离工作或医疗保健太远，不安全，没有公共交通服务，或者距离孩子或家人太远。受访者还提到了住房歧视、在寻找合适的经济适用住房方面缺乏支持、住房等待时间长达数年、缺乏住房券以及药物滥用（包括在街上使用药物保持清醒和警惕）等障碍。<br><br>无家可归就像慢慢地从山上滚下来。在某人跌倒（或失去住房）后立即是提供帮助的最佳时机：在他们经历创伤和不稳定事件<em>之前</em>。在他们出现或恶化药物滥用问题<em>之前</em>。在他们用尽家人和朋友愿意提供的所有帮助<em>之前</em>。在他们上班迟到太多次，或者没有干净衣服上班<em>之前</em>。<br><br>但即使是一个运作良好、资金充足、及早干预的无家可归机构也无法结束无家可归危机，因为无家可归危机就是<em>家庭</em>危机。<br><br>对于即将从与大家庭共同居住的过度拥挤的公寓中被驱逐的人来说，房屋的中位价意味着什么？实际上很多。一条住房链连接着低收入住房、中等收入住房和高收入住房。当新的市场价格单位首次推出并且人们搬进其中时，这会释放他们以前居住的房屋（通常较旧）的空间。当新住房<em>没有</em>投放市场时，高收入居民就会转向旧住房，从而抬高价格。反过来，中等收入工人转向低收入住房单元，底层的每个人都挤在数量不断减少的经济适用房中，直到有人失去自己的位置。<br><br>加州和全国其他昂贵的州推迟建造更多住房的每一天，都会有一个未来的家庭流落街头。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 13:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[How to Redeem Social Media]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>下一代平台不必犯与上一代平台相同的错误。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/H_vof0lqGCujdBkZHC3jWaNNkI4=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/building_back_social_media_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="巨大的岩石拇指，里面长出一朵花" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> Twitter 的缓慢崩溃激发了许多潜在的继任者的灵感。数百万人正在尝试新的社交媒体平台，例如 Meta 的 Threads，热情战胜了经验。<em>我确信，为一个不负责任的亿万富翁运营的社交媒体平台创建免费内容，这次会产生不同的结果</em>，我们告诉自己，就好像我们都是昨天出生的一样。<br><br>我们知道这个故事的结局。我们知道，Facebook 和 Twitter 等平台一开始是令人愉快的联系和对话场所，然后分裂成由可疑病毒内容主导的超极化亚文化，党派成员在各自对立的回声室中互相尖叫。过去如此，将来也将如此。<br><br>除非社交媒体公司有意识地决定以不同的方式做事。这个过渡时刻也是一个机遇时刻，他们有机会重新构想社交媒体的面貌。 Threads 和 Bluesky 等新平台仍在建设中，这意味着它们仍然会受到影响，社会的选择仍然是开放的。这些网站不必复制以前的内容，并且可以从过去的错误中吸取教训。较旧的平台依靠煽动性参与来提高短期利润，但这种选择最终从内部破坏了社交网络，疏远了用户和广告商。如今的平台可以通过旨在建立信任而不是削弱信任的新规则和功能来吸引下一代用户，从而确保网站的长期生存能力。<br><br>以下是我自己的一些建议。该清单并不详尽，理性的人无疑会不同意其中的一些建议。但我希望我们都能同意这次对话的必要性，以及在再次拥抱社交媒体之前重新思考我们想要从社交媒体中得到什么的必要性。<br><br>制定道路规则。<br><br>多年来，Facebook 允许否认大屠杀<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/10/12/923002012/facebook-bans-holocaust-denial-reversing-earlier-policy">——直到它不再这样做</a>。几个月来，Twitter <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://reason.com/2023/01/02/under-government-pressure-twitter-suppressed-truthful-speech-about-covid-19/">一直在压制</a>一系列有关 COVID-19 的言论——有些是虚假的，有些只是有争议的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/11/29/1139822833/twitter-covid-misinformation-policy-not-enforced">——直到它不再出现为止</a>。这两个平台都禁止了唐纳德·特朗普，然后又改变了方向。与此同时，那些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/zlj517/status/1238111898828066823">暗示</a>COVID-19 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/SpokespersonCHN/status/1258780531707109377">起源</a>于美国并试图<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-uses-youtube-and-twitter-to-spread-its-propaganda-version-of-life-for-uyghurs-in-xinjiang">掩盖</a>其政权对维吾尔穆斯林的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/the-uyghur-chronicles/">可怕镇压的</a>中国官员大多都没有受到惩罚。问题不在于 Twitter 或 Facebook 等社交媒体公司对其内容进行了审核。问题在于他们的流程不透明且看似反复无常，而且决策的确切依据很少向公众披露。这种专断的管理非但没有培育出健康的在线社区，反而滋生了不信任。<br><br>相反，我们需要的是一套透明的、详细的标准来管理停职、禁令和其他惩罚，这些标准必须得到明确解释、定期更新和一致应用。社交媒体平台通常会将这些决定的具体细节保密，因为他们希望避免引发争议。但将审核变成黑匣子却引发了另一种形式的争议。由于用户永远无法确切地知道为什么某些内容被删除或压制，这些平台很容易成为怀疑、偏执和偏见指控的目标。确实，没有一套公共节制原则能让所有人满意。但这是一个功能，而不是一个错误。用户将可以根据平台是否符合自己的理想来选择把时间花在哪里，平台将不再被用户不断抱怨自己的待遇所困扰。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/03/social-media-algorithms-twitter-meta-rss-reader/673282/">Yair Rosenberg：如何重新控制您在互联网上阅读的内容</a><br><br><strong>拥抱无常和隐私。</strong><br><br>现实世界的对话和社交媒体互动的区别在于，网络版本是永恒的，这使得个人很难超越过去的自己和最愚蠢的言论。年轻人尤其容易在网上过度分享，常常表现出他们与年龄相称的无知和不成熟。在互联网出现之前，随着一个人进入成年期，青春期的这一自然部分就会逐渐消失。然而如今，情况已不再如此，并带来了不良后果——而且不仅仅是对青少年而言。在极端情况下，网络攻击考古学家会挖掘人们的个人资料，寻找他们多年前发表的有问题的言论，无论这些情绪是否反映了这个人现在是谁。这创造了一种持续监视和怀疑的文化，并有可能<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/63399d48fb1fdd0036293c1e/yom-kippur-forgiveness-anti-semitism-antepli/">将有前途的人囚禁</a>在最糟糕的版本中，永远因他们最早的错误而蒙上污点。<br><br>为了防止这些问题，平台应该默认存档旧内容，并在一段设定的时间（也许是 30 天）后让其他人无法访问这些内容，该时间可以由用户调整。旧帖子对于那些制作它们的人来说仍然是可读的，但对于陌生人和搜索引擎来说却无法访问。社交媒体可能再次成为一种对话，评论不再被理解为个人对某个主题的最后一句话，而是作为一个人不断进化的一部分。尽管这项政策可能允许一些杰出人物归档他们过去不那么令人愉快的部分，但对于那些不应该陷入最低谷的普通人来说，这种成本所带来的好处超过了这一成本。<br><br><strong>结束趋势。</strong><br><br>过去一周，“犹太人”一直是推特上的热门话题。这并不是因为人们钦佩他们对美国冰淇淋行业<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/the-jewish-history-of-americas-most-famous-ice-creams/">的巨大贡献</a>。这是因为极右帐户一直在分享反犹太主义内容。公众对犹太人的好色迷恋早在社交媒体之前就已经存在，但定期在侧边栏上展示它是一种选择。 Twitter 的“趋势”部分旨在捕捉用户当前正在讨论的所有内容，但在实践中，它常常放大了平台的病态，将用户引导至病毒式传播和人为加剧的骗局。<br><br>这些问题可以通过人为调节得到部分改善，但这需要人力和文化能力，而且这些决定会不断引发争议。赢得这场游戏的唯一方法就是不玩，让用户谈论他们喜欢的内容，而不刺激他们进行不相关的对话或激励追逐潮流的内容。在线激进主义也将摆脱主题标签活动的怪异控制，这些活动以其知名度吸引了组织，但不一定能带来回报。<br><br><strong>禁止世界领导人，或者至少禁止本国人民使用社交媒体的领导人。</strong><br><br>无论是特朗普煽动国会大厦骚乱，还是伊朗最高领袖一边<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/khamenei_ir/status/446928689943420928?lang=fi">否认</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/khamenei_ir/status/1321494146989907969">大屠杀</a>一边<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Yair_Rosenberg/status/1534560786462416897">煽动</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Yair_Rosenberg/status/1552450234210459650">反犹太主义</a>，国家元首往往是社交媒体平台最头疼的问题。由于这些人的言论本质上具有新闻价值，因此即使他们最极端的言论受到缓和也会带来问题，无论他们的话的潜在后果有多么危险。正如特朗普的例子所表明的那样，有关政治领导人的具体决定会受到指控和争议，并且不可避免地会在平台上遭到反击。解决方案是首先不要让他们进入网站。这些政客并不是缺乏其他传达信息的选择。更重要的是，让他们远离社交媒体也会产生有益的效果，鼓励他们为自己的实际选民工作，而不是为无定形的在线观众表演。你可以担任总统，也可以担任总统，但不能两者兼而有之。<br><br> <a href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/62a11ef0582ffb002082bd49/iran-ayatollah-ali-khamenei-twitter-anti-semitism/">Yair Rosenberg：为什么 Twitter 不会禁止其最强大的反犹太分子</a><br><br>一个不太雄心勃勃的选择是：如果一个国家限制其公民使用社交媒体网站，则应禁止其政治领导人和外交官使用该平台。目前，中国和伊朗的独裁政权封锁了本国人民的脸书和推特，同时允许本国官员使用这些平台进行宣传。实际上，这意味着独裁政权能够在社交媒体上为自己的人民说话，而面临的反对最小。展望未来，平台应该让一个国家的官员遵守这些官员对他们镇压的人民施加的相同标准。<br><br>社交媒体<span class="smallcaps"> </span>就被强加给我们的社会，而没有对其影响进行任何深思熟虑。它产生了许多积极的影响，提高了以前闻所未闻的声音并揭露了不公正现象。但它也使我们的集体话语<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">变得粗俗</a>，使我们对复杂问题的讨论变得愚蠢，并培育了一种阴谋主义和持续争议的文化。其中许多失败都是人类的失败，但第一波社交媒体网站的结构<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/elon-musk-twitter-problems-misinformation-bigotry/671952/">加剧了这些失败并奖励了</a>它们。<br><br>最终，这些失败导致了平台的退化，这意味着缓解这些问题符合下一代社交媒体公司的最佳利益。当这些网站首次推出时，它们的所有者并不知道他们会与总统和流行病发生争执。现在他们做到了，是时候吸取过去几十年的教训来重建他们的基础设施了。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[In Praise of Phone Numbers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>互联网提供了许多新的沟通方式，但没有什么比 10 位数的电话号码更重要的了。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/a52YFmgtdZ3O1Ip79Zxz6dKtA6E=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/phone_numbers/original.png" alt="一只手拿着手机" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/《大西洋月刊》插图</figcaption></figure>想象一下一种简单、通用且无需软件更新的技术。它是一串数字，每个部分都充当一组精确的坐标 - 如此基本和优雅，以至于您的曾祖父母可以使用它。将数字按正确的顺序排列，这项技术就会立即触发一点魔力：几秒钟前还一片寂静，触觉上一片空白，突然之间，数英里甚至是大陆之外，突然爆发出一阵美妙的声音或振动。然后，如果你幸运的话，你会听到一个声音，然后你用你的声音回应：你的问题，你沮丧地请求与“代表”交谈！<br><br>自 1879 年以来，电话号码一直以某种形式存在于我们身边，与复写纸、VHS 磁带和随身听不同，它尚未过时。尽管现在有数十种联系方式，但很少有像拿起电话一样持久可靠。一个快速的思维实验：假设你刚刚遭遇了车祸，或者，上帝保佑，发现自己真的处于紧急情况——你会发短信寻求帮助，还是会拨打紧急联系人或 911？尽管我们的大部分身份已经转移到网上，但这些数字序列是与物理世界的模拟联系。当我们创建帐户或需要向任何给定的机器和网络系统证明我们的身份时，我们使用数字字符串作为身份验证手段。<br><br>但电话号码不仅是技术领域的自耕农——一种谦虚、实用的主力——它也是一块重要的文化试金石。我一直是一个没有国家的人；由于童年时的搬迁和成年后普遍的不安，他有幸收养了许多家乡，从曼哈顿到蒙大拿州的米苏拉。尽管我在徘徊，但我的地方感和我身份的一个重要方面却永远固定下来，这要归功于三个简单的号码： <em>610</em> ，这是“费城郊区”的总机电话<em>。</em> “我在那里只住了十年，但就是在那时我碰巧得到了我的第一部手机。因此，我的区号为我提供了类似于巧妙伪装甚至护照的东西。偶然发现另一个 610 号码就像打开一扇门一样。<em>你来自哪个城镇？噢，真的，你在哪里上学？</em>三位数可以把陌生人变成同路人。<br><br>电话号码，太棒了！一个伟大的发明，十分之十，没有注释！<em>打电话给 JG 温特沃斯！ 877-立即现金！ 800-588-2300，帝国（今天）！</em>如果没有电话号码我们会在哪里？无聊的？丢失的？穿着缠腰布，在明火上烤新鲜猎取的肉？ 2003 年的一天，我无意中走出了一个热门话题，走进普鲁士国王购物中心的一家 Cingular Wireless 商店，看到了一个几乎是随机的 10 位数指示符，这让我不禁感到有点浪漫。我仍然习惯在凌晨 1 点登录我的银行，联系兽医，并在我的群聊中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/realteaemoji/status/1679173275002322972?s=20">发送令人不安的人工智能生成的 TikTok</a> ，这就是持久力<em>和</em>多功能性。<br><br>在我 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/cwarzel/status/1641161893904793600">发布</a>关于电话号码在我们生活中所扮演的角色的推文后，许多人回复并分享了他们自己的观点。电话号码可以标志着一个新的场合，就像一位名叫 Austin McKinley 的用户所做的那样，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thebadcode/status/1641514561009483776?s=20">告诉</a>我，他 2008 年搬到旧金山时做的第一件事就是购买一部 iPhone 并获得一个本地电话号码。 “旧的生活结束了，新的生活开始了，”他写道。在缅因州（以及我以前的蒙大拿州）等地方，区号可能意味着国家自豪感。 “拥有非 207 号码是局外人的直接信号，”推特用户、迈纳州人本·斯普拉格 (Ben Sprague) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/bensprague/status/1641167129645809664?s=20">告诉</a>我。 “那些远离区号歧视的人有祸了。”一个好的号码也可以是与过去的情感纽带，因为它适用于一位位于费城、名叫艾米的用户，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/theHollandaise/status/1641164293746958336?s=20">告诉</a>我，她在母亲去世时继承了她的号码。我的朋友约翰在推特上的昵称是约翰尼·勇气（Johnny Courage），他写道，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/johnnycourage/status/1641296385361301504?s=20">保留</a>了自己的 919 区号，以“保持我在卡罗来纳州的真诚和南方侨民身份”。 “当然，这是昨天的古雅遗迹。但它把我和家联系在一起。”<br><br>这些老式的乐趣并不意味着电话号码没有随着时间的推移而演变。正如我的同事梅根·加伯 (Megan Garber) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">在 2014 年所写的那样</a>，电话号码最初是服务于较小地理区域的特殊字母数字地址（例如，她写道，MU 5-9975 会将您引导至总机代理，然后由该代理将您与纽约市默里山 (Murray Hill) 社区）。随着电话越来越普及，手动总机系统变得自动化，号码系统从地区性转向全国性，号码组更长，并引入了区号。每次编号系统扩展时，我们都会抱怨，但它仍然持续存在——北美当前的 10 位编号系统于 1997 年在马里兰州<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/23/technology/the-10-or-11-digit-local-call-fosters-anxiety-and-shrugs.html">推出</a>，我们没有回头。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">阅读：区号的演变</a><br><br>但即使是 10 位数字系统（我生活中的技术常数之一）也有过期日期。在某些时候，这些数字将会耗尽，这一认识让我想知道谁（如果有人）在密切关注我们的数字。值得庆幸的是，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nationalnanpa.com/about_us/index.html">北美编号计划管理员（North American Numbering Plan Administrator）</a>是一个令人愉快的官僚组织，负责管理和分配 20 个国家/地区的电话号码和区号。假设一大群人搬到蒙大拿州或缅因州并申请新号码，NANPA 的高级主管 Florence Weber 告诉我，NANPA 的团队与运营商和州委员会合作推出新的区号，这个过程至少需要三年时间。<br><br> “我们继续看到对数字的请求不断增加，而且这种情况不会消失，”韦伯说。但没有什么是永恒的。 NANPA 一直在密切关注并为我们用完三位数区号或必须超越 10 位数区号的那一天做好准备。韦伯告诉我，根据 NANPA 的专有预测系统（该系统考虑了预测需求和分配率），“预计用尽日期”是 2051 年的某个时间。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1880/06/a-telephonic-conversation/306078/">马克·吐温：一次电话交谈（1880 年 6 月起）</a><br><br>一想到那天会发生什么，我就不寒而栗。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/are-12-digit-phone-numbers-in-our-future/">更长的电话号码</a>的出现是一种可能性。屈服于在线服务是另一回事。电话号码感觉有点像 Zoom 会议、一键式 FaceTiming、WhatsApp、Signal、Viber、DM、Discord 等时代的遗物。电话号码最初被认为是一种通过位置路由连接的方式，从技术上讲，互联网现在也可以通过 IP 地址或使用互联网语音协议来实现这一点。书呆子们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pocketnow.com/why-are-we-still-using-phone-numbers/">建议</a>我们可以放弃编号系统，而使用去中心化的呼叫系统，其工作方式有点像网址——你获得一个唯一的地址并购买一个域名，这样人们就可以联系你，而无需输入一长串号码。<br><br>尽管如此，如果我们的区号、前缀和线路号码被时间的沙子慢慢冲走，我们会失去什么，这是值得考虑的。如果没有更多的话，值得欣赏这些数字——一系列非个人的半随机数字，一旦它们属于你，就会获得新的生命。当共享时，电话号码是最亲密的邀请，提供无限的联系可能性。它为我们停泊并引导我们。仅此一点就是一个值得庆祝的小奇迹。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastruct/674735/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastruct/674735/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is Tennessee a Democracy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当共和党获得绝对多数控制权并不满意时会发生什么<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/27TF7e4XH-or1LtfF2cywj_n4xQ=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/17/TheAtlantic_Tennessee_1_jul23_rt/original.jpg" alt="红色的田纳西州议会大厦" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>里卡多·托马斯为《大西洋月刊》拍摄的照片插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br><span class="smallcaps">沿着纳什维尔北部远郊</span>的外缘行驶，经过可能是谷仓或可能是婚礼场地的建筑，围绕葡萄园格罗夫或新希望村的开发项目，最终您将到达本应成为公司新总部的地方。田纳西州萨姆纳县选举委员会。这是一个毫无特色的单层砖砌仓库，附有一些临时办公室，空间只够容纳极少数选举委员会员工、他们最近购买的 275 台投票机，或许还可以容纳一些过去与他们共用房间的维护人员。那时，该机构还在县政府大楼的地下室里。<br><br>布满灰尘的野餐桌靠在墙上。一所小学就在几百米开外。这座建筑或其位置没有什么引起“争议”的。但当去年萨姆纳县的地方选举中一个自称宪政共和党的派别上台时，它却变成了这样。<br><br>为了充分理解这个故事，你需要明白美国政治两极分化的标准形式在萨姆纳并不存在，萨姆纳是一个农村但迅速郊区化的县，民主党根本不参与其中。二十多年来，没有人赢得任何县公职。相反，立宪共和党赢得了县委员会 17 个席位中的 14 个（在大选中只有 15% 的合格选民参加了投票），他们的主要对手是普通共和党人，或者正如他们的对手所说的那样他们，RINO（“名义上的共和党人”）。宪法共和党的网站解释说，绿诺组织与他们自己不同：“他们提高税收，他们投票让公民保持沉默，他们不会保护私有财产权。他们经常与民主党合作，击败像我们这样真正的宪政共和党人。”<br><br>接管县委员会后，立宪共和党<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/election-conspiracies-local-government-religion-republicans-tennessee-758307fb4856c91138c085ad70505841">发布了一份文件，</a>正式宣布他们的活动将“反映建国之初固有的犹太基督教价值观”。他们还关闭了人力资源部门，试图将一栋公共历史建筑私有化，并拒绝支付选举委员会搬迁至砖砌建筑的费用，尽管这是上届政府同意的。旧办公室（最近被洪水淹没的三个地下室）太小，无法存放新的投票机，而且也不安全。我去的那天，地下室的入口就在收银窗口旁边，有几十个人在排队缴税。县专员对这些论点不为所动。 “如果我们不资助它，你就不能这样做，”县委员会的宪法共和党人之一杰里米·曼斯菲尔德(Jeremy Mansfield)在去年秋天的一次公开会议上向选举委员会介绍了这一举措。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYzcIZXfkmI">6 月的一次会议</a>上，另一位县专员因新投票机已交付到新大楼而感到愤怒，他表示，尽管他“不愿意拿出王牌”，但该委员会总是可以“宣布这笔财产剩余，并出售”。它。”这将使选举委员会及其机器无处可去。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-induced-idiocy-tennessee/673726/">彼得·韦纳：田纳西州特朗普主义的猛烈攻击</a><br><br>这座建筑似乎是一件值得大惊小怪的小事。但 Facebook 上的帖子和公开会议的视频都可以在网上查看——立宪共和党人非常透明——清楚地表明这不是一个微不足道的管辖权纠纷，这些人也不是小人。他们的野心和兴趣远远超出了他们的县域。他们的 Facebook 页面对唐纳德·特朗普最新起诉的消息作出反应，宣称“拜登家族是一个有组织的犯罪家族”，“我们的司法系统被操纵来对付特朗普”。另一篇帖子询问田纳西州是否“应该脱离联邦”。更重要的是，曼斯菲尔德没有回应我的采访请求（他对媒体的看法在他的 Facebook 页面上很清楚，有人将美联社称为“美国真理报”，他回答说，“除了《真理报》做了更诚实的报道”），二月份写了一篇长文攻击提前投票和投票机：“选举公正性的黄金标准是由人们填写纸质选票，并在选举日由当地选区的人们进行计票。”<br><br>立宪共和党人对这些观点充满信心是有原因的。 “我们的信仰源自圣经，”他们的网站宣称：“我们在每次聚会上祈祷，并在我们所做的一切事情中寻求上帝！他的智慧指导着我们的决定。” The same source gives them confidence that their enemies are wrong. “Evil never sleeps,” Mansfield wrote on Facebook, after reflecting on the critics who he said were attacking him for fighting against new development in the county, “so we must heed Churchill&#39;s words, never give in, and never give up fighting for what is good and right.”<br><br> Few of these ambitious goals are within their reach. The Sumner County commissioners can&#39;t arrest President Joe Biden. They can&#39;t secede. But the county&#39;s election commission, whose members are appointed by the bipartisan state election commission, is right there. It&#39;s a local embodiment of the broader culture they dislike and of the government they distrust. If they can stick the agency back in the flood-prone basement, they will.<br><br> Tom Lee, the lawyer for the Sumner election commission—it is now suing the county—has an additional explanation as well. Lee points out that the Constitutional Republicans arrived in office wanting to enact deep, revolutionary change. That means that, whatever the previous regime decided, they are against it: “They are coming to power and saying, &#39;Everything that came before us doesn&#39;t count. We represent something new and different, and we don&#39;t have to have any allegiance to the past.&#39;” I told him that this sounded like the language used by the Bolsheviks, among other revolutionaries. He didn&#39;t laugh.<br><br> M <span class="smallcaps">ost of the time</span> , Tennessee politics doesn&#39;t make national news. That changed in April, when the leaders of the Republican supermajority in the Tennessee House of Representatives expelled two Democratic legislators, Justin Jones and Justin Pearson. The two men were accused of disrupting proceedings, because they repeated the demands of gun-control activists on the floor of the chamber, during a recess, using a megaphone.<br><br> The incident created a wave of outrage. The punishment seemed both extreme—since Reconstruction, only two people have been expelled from the Tennessee legislature, one for bribery and the other for alleged sexual misconduct—and racist, because it deliberately targeted two young Black men. A third protester, Representative Gloria Johnson, who is white, was allowed to keep her house seat. Belatedly, the Republicans who made this decision realized that it looked bad. At an acrimonious meeting held afterward (a tape of which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tnholler.com/2023/04/leaked-audio-tn-house-gop-caucus-infighting-over-tn-3-votes/">leaked to <i>The</i> <i>Tennessee Holler</i></a> , a local online publication), they expressed no regret at the expulsions, but they did berate one of the members for not voting to expel Johnson, on the grounds that leaving her out made them all seem like racists. The decision also made heroes of the protesters, now dubbed the Tennessee Three, a title previously bestowed on Johnny Cash&#39;s backup band. Jones and Pearson were reinstated by local officials, pending special elections in August, and became instant national stars.<br><br> But in truth, their story did not start on that day. Not so long ago, Tennessee was not merely a more bipartisan state but a <i>model</i> of bipartisanship, an example to others. Keel Hunt, a columnist for the <i>Tennessean</i> newspaper (and a Democrat who once worked for a Republican governor, Lamar Alexander), wrote a book about the 1980s and &#39;90s, an era when moderate Democrats and liberal Republicans ruled the state; when Tennessee sent Alexander, Howard Baker, Al Gore, and Jim Sasser to the US Senate; and when many of the decisions that paved the way for Tennessee&#39;s current investment boom were made. The book is called <i>Crossing the Aisle: How Bipartisanship Brought Tennessee to the Twenty-First Century and Could Save America</i> . So much has changed since then, Hunt told me, that the book “might now qualify as an obituary.”<br><br> Today, Tennessee is a model of one-party rule. It has a Republican governor and legislature. Republican appointees run the state supreme court. The state&#39;s nine-member US House delegation contains eight Republicans; Tennessee has sent two Republicans to the Senate. The governor is the only other official elected statewide. Unlike in other states, the attorney general and secretary of state in Tennessee are appointed, and they are both Republicans too.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/america-democracy-autocracy-laboratories/673751/">Brian Klaas: The red states experimenting with authoritarianism</a><br><br> Nor will the situation be easy to change, because gerrymandering is something of a blood sport in the state. The still-blue city of Nashville had a single Democrat representing it in Congress, but when the map was redrawn before the 2022 elections, GOP lawmakers split Nashville into three districts that stretch out into the countryside. Each elected a Republican. Instead of Jim Cooper, a Blue Dog moderate Democrat who held the seat for two decades, Nashville is now represented by, among others, Andy Ogles, who is best known for sending out a holiday card featuring himself, his children, and his wife all holding guns in front of a Christmas tree. State-level gerrymandering is just as vicious—Johnson reckons that one redistricting included a special effort to eliminate her from politics: “They split my precinct and drew a line basically a few blocks around my house to draw me out of the district,” she told me. (She moved, ran again, and won.)<br><br> Getting people to vote is not so easy, either, because Tennessee has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">some of the nation&#39;s most restrictive voting laws</a> . You can&#39;t register to vote any later than 30 days before an election. If you vote by absentee ballot, it has to arrive by mail on or before Election Day. There are no drop boxes. First-time voters have to vote in person, which is a special problem for college students studying out of state. In 2019, the legislature passed a law <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">subjecting voter-registration campaigners</a> to financial or criminal penalties if they submit too many erroneous forms—a provision that seemed designed to discourage get-out-the-vote campaigns, was blocked as unconstitutional, and later repealed. Perhaps none of these rules alone would seem outrageous. But the “cumulative effect,” argues Tricia Herzfeld, a Democrat who serves on Nashville&#39;s election commission, “is to make it hard to vote.” There is evidence for that theory: Tennessee has either one of the lowest or else the very lowest voter-turnout rates in the country, depending on how you count. And that, of course, is even before Sumner County moved to deprive its election commission of office space, conceivably making it difficult for anyone there to vote at all.<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">came to Tennessee</span> partly because I wondered how similar it might feel to Poland and Hungary, where for the past decade I&#39;ve been warily observing the decline of democracy and the rise of the one-party state. The very large differences are immediately clear in Nashville, where music is the backdrop to everything, where everyone seems to be coming from a party or heading to one, where people on both sides of the political spectrum went out of their way to introduce me to other people. “This is a son-in-law kind of town,” someone told me. I wasn&#39;t quite sure what that meant (something to do with everyone looking after friends and relatives?), but it was amusing. For that and many other reasons, Nashville is not Budapest-on-the-Cumberland. The Bill of Rights still applies. Federal judges rule on Tennessee laws. The US Constitution is widely and even ostentatiously revered. There is no Central European gloom.<br><br> Nevertheless, the cascade of tiny legal and procedural changes designed to create an unlevel playing field, the ruling party&#39;s inexplicable sense of grievance, the displaced moderates with nowhere to go—this did seem familiar from other places. So was the sense that institutional politics has become performative, somehow separated from real life. The Tennessee Three staged their protest on the floor of the legislature, after all, because the conversation unfolding there had taken no notice of the much larger protests happening outside the chamber. A few days earlier, a horrific mass shooting at Covenant, a private Christian school in Nashville, had galvanized the public. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2023/05/03/vanderbilt-poll-tennessee/">Opinion polls</a> showed that more than 70 percent of Tennesseans want red-flag laws that would allow officials to remove guns from people who might misuse them, while more than 80 percent support background checks and other gun-safety laws.<br><br> Those enormous majorities were not reflected in the legislative debate. In the days following the school shooting, it was just “business as usual,” Justin Kanew, the founder and editor of <i>The Tennessee Holler</i> , told me. Kanew, a transplant from California like a number of people in Nashville, is himself a former Democratic candidate for Congress in Tennessee. During his campaign, he saw a gap in the public conversation, and that experience led him to found the <i>Holler</i> . Or rather the Hollers: There are now several Twitter offshoots—the Chattanooga Holler, the Clarksville Holler, and so on—all focused on the hyperlocal issues that the statewide media were missing. Kanew&#39;s own talent is for a form of campaigning journalism: He produces short video clips, often of state legislators, and then circulates them on social media. Sometimes they go viral. That&#39;s what he was doing on the day the Tennessee Three made their protest. “There were thousands of people showing up at the capitol,” he told me, “asking for something to happen. And if nothing had happened, that would have been pretty deflating.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/04/tennessee-expulsions-republican-gop/673709/">Read: The Tennessee expulsions are just the beginning</a><br><br> This was not the first time that the Republican leadership sought to shut down debate. The house&#39;s “two Justins,” as they are now known, brought their megaphone precisely because the Republican leadership commonly turns off Democrats&#39; microphones when they are speaking. Representative Bo Mitchell was once cut off when he told the house, “Please don&#39;t say you are pro-life and put more weapons on the street”—a statement ruled to be insulting. Jones told me that he was ruled out of order during a committee meeting because he&#39;d said the leadership was “putting a Band-Aid on the issue” of school shootings; a few days later he was also told he had to remove a <span class="smallcaps">ban assault weapons</span> pin from his jacket. Republicans insist, as Tennessee House Majority Leader William Lamberth <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/NC5PhilWilliams/status/1661524250019201024?s=20">told a local television station</a> , that speakers are meant to stick to the topic: “It&#39;s not open-mic night.”<br><br> “They are coming to power and saying, &#39;Everything that came before us doesn&#39;t count. We represent something new and different, and we don&#39;t have to have any allegiance to the past.&#39;”<br><br> Under relatively recent rules, individual members&#39; question time has been cut from 15 minutes to five. Occasionally, people who want to raise objections are not called on at all. During a debate on a bill regulating abortion, Gloria Johnson told me, “I stood on the house floor for 45 minutes, the entire argument of the bill, and they refused to call on me.” These tactics are new. Johnson, who has served in the legislature on and off for more than a decade, told me that although the house also had a Republican supermajority when she joined in 2012, the speaker at that time didn&#39;t exclude Democrats from debate. “I don&#39;t recall her refusing to call on me,” she said. Jones, who was a community organizer in Nashville for a decade before being elected, agreed that previous speakers were more open to conversation. “This was the most extreme session I have ever seen,” he said. “Republicans now treat the legislature as a private palace, a fraternity house or a country club.”<br><br> Nor is radicalization visible only in the legislature. Just as Hungary&#39;s Viktor Orbán fights with opposition-controlled Budapest (and Turkey&#39;s Recep Tayyip Erdoğan fights with Istanbul, and Poland&#39;s Jarosław Kaczyński fights with Warsaw), so do Tennessee Republicans fight with opposition-controlled Nashville. Over breakfast at the Elliston Place Soda Shop—he likes showing off the city sites—Nashville Mayor John Cooper, a Democrat (and brother of Jim Cooper, the former member of Congress), ticked off the various disputes between the city and the state with a certain level of weariness: about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/04/03/faa-intervenes-in-dispute-over-nashville-airport-leadership/70076289007/">control over the airport</a> , about the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.adamsandreese.com/last-call/fate-of-metro-nashville-beer-board-remains-uncertain-at-tennessee-general-assembly">beer board</a> , about the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/03/09/bills-to-take-over-nashville-airport-sports-authority-boards-advance/69985037007/">sports authority</a> , about the size of the city council (Republicans tried to cut it from 40 members to 20), and about the 2024 Republican National Convention—which, partly thanks to all of the other quarrels, will not take place in Nashville.<br><br> Some of the disputes are just about who controls the money, but he thinks real cultural friction underlies those too. Whereas Nashville used to be what the mayor calls a “big county-seat kind of town,” famous for its music clubs, now it&#39;s also a focus of international investment, health-care investment, and tech investment. Oracle is building a $1 billion–plus campus in the city; Amazon has a major presence here too. On the morning we met, Mayor Cooper was jet-lagged, having just returned from Kurdistan. He went there because Nashville, aside from being the city that launched Taylor Swift, is also home to one of the largest Kurdish communities in America. After breakfast, he drove me to the East Bank, the site of the city&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nashville.gov/departments/planning/long-range-planning/local-planning-studies/east-bank-planning-study">next major development project</a> , one that will include a new stadium, new housing, and some infrastructure renovations; along the way, we passed a remarkable collection of building sites, replete with giant cranes. Still, in the conservative mediaverse, Nashville&#39;s city leaders are just another set of enemies. Fox News once devoted a whole segment to Cooper—in which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/virus-outbreak-marsha-blackburn-nashville-tucker-carlson-tennessee-d8370b1bab309d954a8b6b7fb5547d39">Tucker Carlson accused him, falsely</a> , of concealing information about COVID.<br><br> Kanew (and he isn&#39;t alone) thinks the state serves as a kind of “guinea pig,” a test market in this same mediaverse, a place where new culture-war themes can be experimentally stoked. A war on judges as well as on remote voting began in 2021, when the chair of a key house subcommittee <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2021/03/02/support-grows-nashville-judge-ellen-hobbs-lyle-targeted-lawmaker/6878391002/">sought to remove a judge</a> who had ruled in favor of expanding the right to vote by mail during the pandemic. Last September, the governor and other Republicans <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/">lashed out at Vanderbilt University Medical Center</a> , allegedly for suppressing employees who criticized the university&#39;s gender clinic, charges the university denied. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/"> </a>More recently, the state attorney general has investigated the clinic, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tennesseelookout.com/2023/06/22/ag-made-sweeping-demands-for-vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-records-as-part-of-fraud-inquiry/?eType=EmailBlastContent&amp;eId=0bdfc350-1039-4564-94e1-7a42e32a226c">demanding private medical records</a> .<br><br> Sometimes these efforts are clawed back. A determined group of local lawyers and lobbyists helped get some exceptions for the life of the mother enshrined into the state&#39;s abortion ban. A Trump-appointed federal judge <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/13/opinion/tennessee-trump-maga-justin-jones-pearson.html">recently overturned</a> another culture-war gesture, a Tennessee law banning public drag performances, on the grounds that it chilled free speech. But whether individual pieces of hard-line legislation stick might not matter, because part of the point of passing them is just to allow local politicians to align themselves with the general views of that same conservative mediaverse. One example: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://trackbill.com/bill/tennessee-senate-joint-resolution-174-memorials-recognition-danube-institute/2353243/">a recent resolution</a> passed by the legislature to “recognize and commend” Orbán&#39;s think tank, the Danube Institute, which promotes illiberal and antidemocratic ideas. Jones, objecting to that resolution, asked Tim Hicks, the Republican who proposed it, if he knew who Orbán was. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thetnholler/status/1648811745064935425?s=46&amp;t=QfucpGynsbxt5jS-672ayA">He did not</a> . One disgruntled Republican described this whole process to me as “governing by anecdote.” You could also describe it as “governing by Fox News.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/01/children-sex-trafficking-conspiracy-epidemic/620845/">From the January/February 2022 issue: The great (fake) child-sex-trafficking epidemic</a><br><br> But every so often, a glimpse of something uglier appears, a hint that some people want more than culture wars designed for TikTok, Twitter, and the evening news. Walking to her home in Nashville, an acquaintance saw a car with a <span class="smallcaps">shoot your local pedophile</span><i> </i>bumper sticker, showing an outline of a man holding a gun to another man&#39;s head. T-shirts with this image, phrasing, and implied approval of violence are for sale online. “This isn&#39;t new to you, but it&#39;s new to us,” she told me, which isn&#39;t quite true. Poland, where I live part of the time, has had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46878325">one political murder</a> in recent years, but it was a knife murder. In Tennessee, people have guns. Jim Cooper, the former member of Congress, told me that getting anyone to run for office as a Democrat in some rural parts of the state is difficult partly because <i>Democrat</i> and <i>pedophile</i> are so often conflated by Republican activists, and potential candidates are spooked. About half of the state-legislature seats were uncontested in 2022.<br><br> Not that the problem of finding Democrats to run for office is new. Cooper also told me that one of his staff used to comb through local newspapers and look for people who had written angry letters to the editor. Then she would call them up and ask them to stand for election. Some said yes. Though most of them lost, he considered that a kind of victory. Jones thinks that after the expulsion crisis, “young people are fired up, bringing urgency to our politics,” and that more candidates will come forward. But there will be a steep road to climb if people fear that what is at stake in their local election is not tax rates and building permits but the safety and even the lives of their children—and if they fight back with real weapons.<br><br> If that possibility sounds ludicrous, or incredible, it shouldn&#39;t. Kanew, the <i>Tennessee Holler</i> editor, woke up one night last April to the sound of gunfire. Someone had shot up the front of his house. No one has yet been arrested.<br><br> “Y <span class="smallcaps">ou know the old saying:</span> All politics is national.” That&#39;s what the mayor of Nashville told me over his ham and eggs. “All politics is national,” several other people said to me too. It&#39;s a joke—“All politics is local” is the old political chestnut—but also not a joke. In the past couple of years, prominent and less-prominent conservatives have been flocking from all over the country to Tennessee and, more precisely, to Williamson County, adjacent to Nashville and, partly thanks to that proximity, now one of the wealthiest counties in the country. The town of Franklin, Williamson&#39;s county seat, has a large and well-lit (I visited at night) monument to the soldiers of the Confederacy. It is also home to equally monumental culture-war clashes and school-board battles that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/23/opinion/school-boards-books-tennessee.html">can rival those anywhere else in the country</a> . The <i>New York Times</i> columnist David French, who lives there, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/06/opinion/maga-america-trump.html">reckons</a> that “only 15 percent of my neighbors are Democrats.” The Daily Wire, a conservative media company that specializes in culture-war clashes and school-board battles, is now based in Nashville, as are a handful of its stars.<br><br> Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should.<br><br> “All politics is national” is also the explanation that a lot of people gave me when I asked how Tennessee went from having a culture of bipartisanship to de facto one-party rule in a mere two decades. Almost everybody wanted to explain that Tennessee politics used to reflect the state&#39;s particular geography (mountains in the east, Mississippi River Delta in the west, rivers and forest in the middle) and complicated history. Some Tennesseans had declared for the Confederacy; others fought against it. The Ku Klux Klan was founded in Pulaski, Tennessee; Nashville was the site of a series of sit-ins that were important to the civil-rights movement. The disgruntled Republicans in particular <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnas.org/publications/blog/two-cheers-for-tennessee">mourn the death</a> of what used to be called “Tennessee enlightened mountain Republicanism,” the liberal, business-oriented party that once challenged the pre-civil-rights “Old South” Democratic one-party state, which relied on Jim Crow and voter suppression. For a long time, both parties celebrated the demise of that system, and no one wanted it back. Or so it seemed.<br><br> By some accounts, the shift began in the 1990s, during the Clinton administration, when talk radio and a confrontational new style of national media began to weaken the local newspapers that people used to read, and the local culture too. Others think the turning point came in the 2000s, when Barack Obama&#39;s presidency produced a racist backlash. In 2012, one poll showed that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/sorry-obama-birtherism-is-alive-and-well-2012-3?IR=T">nearly half of Tennessee Republicans</a> believed in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/05/birtherism-and-trump/610978/">birtherism conspiracy theory</a> .<br><br> Still others think the harder shift inside the Republican Party began more recently, <i>after</i> it gained full control. John Geer, a Vanderbilt political scientist, told me that whenever a supermajority controls a legislature for a long period of time, “those in the minority have no political ability to effect change, and so they stop acting like politicians and instead become activists,” a thesis that explains the actions of the Tennessee Three, as well as the feeling that politics has become a form of performance art, only distantly related to real life.<br><br> But the supermajority is also affected, and its members become activists of a different kind. To stay in office in a state where few people vote and districts are gerrymandered, Tennessee legislators need to appeal to only a tiny number of very dedicated, very partisan people. The competition for those votes can quite quickly turn into a competition for who can sound most radical. Even the minority leader of the Tennessee State Senate, Raumesh Akbari, a Democrat, told me that it&#39;s harder to do deals with people from heavily gerrymandered districts: “You don&#39;t have anybody to check you and your district is extremely partisan.” Her own district skews heavily Democratic and heavily Black. “If I wasn&#39;t someone who was willing to compromise, I wouldn&#39;t have to,” Akbari said.<br><br> There is another element: Call it the lesson of Sumner County, the place where Republicans won everything, control everything, and yet <i>still</i> feel aggrieved and victimized. As in Hungary or Poland or as in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/venezuelas-suffering-shows-where-illiberalism-leads/606988/">Venezuela</a> , the experience of radicalism can make people more radical. Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should. No county commission or state legislature can possibly meet the demands of a quasi-religious movement that believes it has God on its side and that its opponents herald the apocalypse. But that doesn&#39;t mean they give up. It just means they keep trying, using any tool available. Eventually they arrive at the point described by Tom Lee, the lawyer for the Sumner County Election Commission: “It&#39;s not enough to get your majority and get your way—they have to make the minority lose their voice.”<br><br> On the tape leaked to <i>The</i> <i>Tennessee Holler</i> after the expulsion of Pearson and Jones, this dynamic is powerfully revealed. Grim Republican legislators talked about what they think is really at stake, and it isn&#39;t megaphones. “If you don&#39;t believe we are at war for our republic,” one of them says to the group, “with all love and respect to you, you need a different job.” They don&#39;t believe that this is a normal political competition, either, or that their opponents are a normal, legitimate, small- <i>d</i> democratic opposition. Democrats, says another, “are not our friends.” They “destroy our republic and the foundation of who we are.” At one point, an apocalyptic tone creeps into the conversation: “The left wants Tennessee so bad because if they get us, the Southeast falls and it&#39;s &#39;game over&#39; for the republic.” So urgent and so dramatic is this challenge that some of them have come to believe that rules might have to be broken: “You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong,” one of them says.<br><br> <i>You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong. Fight for the republic</i> , <i>because otherwise it will be “game over</i> ”: The language itself wouldn&#39;t be unusual, if this were a radical minority fighting for its very existence. But this is the Republican Party, the party that controls pretty much everything in Tennessee. They are going to win the next election, and probably the one after that. Yet they sound as if winning isn&#39;t enough: They also want their opponents to fall silent, and they are doing what they can to make that happen.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Remote-Work Debate Stays So Heated]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The conversation often foregrounds large-scale issues such as productivity and company culture, but the question of where an employee works is intensely personal. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C9uTFuz-5brHPsAys00WYgH6Pc8=/0x266:5121x3147/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_862664210/original.jpg" alt="People pass a building at night" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Peter Cade / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i>This is an edition of</i> The Atlantic <i>Daily, a newsletter that guides you through the biggest stories of the day, helps you discover new ideas, and recommends the best in culture.</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>Sign up for it here.</i></a></small><br><br> The physical space in which a person works, or hopes to work, intersects with their most personal choices. Today we&#39;re checking in on the remote-work debate and why it remains so heated.<br><br> First, here are four new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">The businessmen broke Hollywood.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">Goodbye to the prophets of doom.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/">I have cancer. I can&#39;t put my kids first anymore.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/">Joe Lieberman weighs the Trump risk.</a></li> <strong>Better Together?</strong><br><br> In the summer of 2021, I started going back to the office. It was not the allure of watercooler chatter or the promise of juiced-up productivity that pulled me in. At the time, I just really wanted to sit in the AC. It was June; it was hot. Access to a desk in a freezing-cold Midtown tower—a far cry from my living room, which tended to get steamy on 90-degree Brooklyn days—seemed like a major perk. I was living with roommates, was vaccinated, and had no child-care duties. Each morning, I strapped on my mask and packed my backpack with canisters of coffee and sandwiches to sustain me through the day. I often felt better when I got home: When you&#39;re going into an office, I found, it&#39;s harder to have a day where nothing happens.<br><br> My desire to return to a routine that involved leaving my home was inspired, in part, by my now-colleague Ellen Cushing&#39;s 2021 <i>Atlantic</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/03/what-pandemic-doing-our-brains/618221/">article</a> about what the monotony of the pandemic was doing to our brain. “Sometimes I imagine myself as a Sim, a diamond-shaped cursor hovering above my head as I go about my day. Tasks appear, and I do them. Mealtimes come, and I eat. Needs arise, and I meet them,” she writes in one memorable passage. In another, she quotes an expert saying that “environmental enrichment”—seeing new people, observing new things on a commute—is good for our brain&#39;s plasticity. After reading the article in March 2021, I became fixated on the idea that observing random humans on my commute would keep my mind sharp.<br><br> Then the fall came around, and so did more of my colleagues. It was great to see them. It was also great, sometimes, to return to the relative solitude of my home and take walks in Prospect Park at midday. I was lucky to have that flexibility. Now that I work for <i>The Atlantic</i> , I go into the office almost every day. I have enjoyed meeting new people and, again, sitting in the industrial-grade AC.<br><br> I&#39;ve given you this narration of my personal experience because, for all the talk of productivity and metrics and company culture, the topic of returning to the office is intensely personal. My needs and desires, for a variety of reasons relating to my age, finances, circumstances, health situation, and lifestyle, might be very different from those of workers who fall elsewhere on any of those axes. Some working parents have said they might value flexibility at school-pickup time. Some workers of color have raised the benefit of being free from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://hbr.org/2022/05/research-the-real-time-impact-of-microaggressions">in-office microaggressions</a> . Recent college graduates may want to go into the office to make friends. And of course, not all workers are able to work remotely. The physical space in which one works, or hopes to work, intersects with one&#39;s most personal choices. It collides with and reveals what people value most.<br><br> Nick Bloom, a Stanford economics professor who studies remote work, told me that “research and evidence are slowly catching up” to the work-from-home debate. In five years, he predicted, the topic will be less controversial. Bloom and two colleagues, Jose Maria Barrero and Steven J. Davis, published a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kqbngD8pemqxAkZmWCOQ32Yk6PXK9eVA/view">working paper</a> earlier this month that collects some of the existing work-from-home research, pulling both from their own work and from other papers. One interesting finding is that although fully remote work has been correlated with a drop in productivity, hybrid work (which occurs widely in white-collar fields such as tech and business services) was not linked to any productivity loss—and could actually <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://siepr.stanford.edu/publications/working-paper/evolution-working-home">help with recruitment and retention</a> .<br><br> Workers gained freedom over their working conditions in the past few years. Now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/20/business/return-to-office-remote-work.html">many bosses</a> are trying to wrest that power back. And workers and managers don&#39;t always see eye to eye about the stakes of returning to work. Bloom and his colleagues asked managers and employees about how working from home affected productivity. Workers, on the whole, said they were 7.4 percent more productive on average while working from home; bosses said that they thought their employees were 3.5 percent less productive. Managers tend to most appreciate what they can see in front of them, Bloom told me over email: “It&#39;s like those restaurants where the kitchen is open and on display—it feels more like you are having a fantastic culinary experience, but it&#39;s really just a mirage.”<br><br> Companies&#39; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/31/business/work-home-return-office-amazon.html">rationales</a> for calling people back to work can seem mushy, beyond that it simply seems like being together would be better (or, in some cases, that employers want to fulfill expensive real-estate obligations). One argument for working in person is the idea that younger workers can learn from, and be mentored by, more experienced colleagues in the workplace. Bloom told me that senior managers over the age of 50 provide about 50 percent of the mentoring minutes when working from home as they do while in the office. “A lot of mentoring is casual, relaxed conversations and, yes, it&#39;s spontaneous—taking somebody aside and giving some quick advice,” he said. A Pew Research Center survey from March found that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/03/30/about-a-third-of-us-workers-who-can-work-from-home-do-so-all-the-time/">36 percent of teleworkers</a> said remote work hurt their opportunities to be mentored. Positive remote mentoring can happen (I found a formal mentorship program conducted mostly over Zoom very useful). Bloom said that although in theory—and with the right software—these types of relationships can blossom, “practically this does not happen as much online.”<br><br> Bloom&#39;s point (and my reaction to it) reinforces how personal experience can color perspectives on this issue: In my case, I both relish time away from home and believe in the potential of remote mentor relationships. But how those dimensions of work fit into our lives can vary widely. Change any inputs—personal commute time, age, nature of work, child-care responsibilities, goals—and the resulting approach may be unrecognizable.<br><br> <b>Related</b> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/us-remote-work-impact-fertility-rate-babies/673301/">The surprising effects of remote work</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/good-management-mentorship-remote-world/621219/">How to mentor young workers in a remote world</a></li> <strong>Today&#39;s News</strong><br><br><li> Russia is halting the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/17/world/europe/ukraine-russia-grain-deal.html">Black Sea Grain Initiative</a> , which ensured that Ukraine could export its grain by sea despite a wartime blockade and helped stabilize global food prices.</li><li> Senator Joe Manchin&#39;s decision to headline an event with the No Labels organization is <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-senator-manchin-speech-stokes-speculation-white-house-run-2023-07-17/">fueling speculation</a> over a potential third-party presidential run.</li><li> Firefighters are <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/16/us/california-wildfires-extreme-heat/index.html">battling several wildfires</a> in Southern California that ignited this weekend amid excessive heat warnings.</li> <b>Evening Read</b><br><br> Do Yourself a Favor and Go Find a &#39;Third Place&#39;<br><br> <em>By Allie Conti</em><br><br><p> On a Sunday last year, I was walking through a suburban neighborhood in Pennsylvania, heading home from an early-afternoon meditation class. One of the nondescript stucco houses had a curious sticker on its mailbox reading mac&#39;s club. I checked Google Maps to see if I was standing next to a cleverly disguised business—what might pretentiously be referred to in a city as a speakeasy—but nothing popped up, so I peeked inside the house. That&#39;s where I spotted a pool table and a middle-aged guy sitting at the end of a long, mahogany bar, drinking a Bloody Mary by himself. Apparently I&#39;d stumbled upon a social club meant for residents of the neighborhood. Though at first the bartender was incredulous that I&#39;d just walked in, he soon rewarded my sense of adventure with a Guinness on the house. The Eagles weren&#39;t playing in the NFL that day, and he was grateful for the additional company. We talked about the upcoming deer season, and upon learning that I was a new hunter, the two guys showed me a rifle that was kept in another room. ……</p><p> Besides giving me the feeling that I&#39;d flexed a muscle that had atrophied, the interaction was special to me because I&#39;d found a classic “third place” in the suburbs, where I least expected it. The term, which was coined by the sociologist Ray Oldenburg in the 1980s, essentially refers to a physical location other than work or home where there&#39;s little to no financial barrier to entry and where conversation is the primary activity.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/04/third-places-meet-new-people-pandemic/629468/">Read the full article.</a><br><br> <b>More From <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/">Elizabeth Bruenig: Alabama wants to kill Jimi Barber.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/">The most shocking aspect of RFK Jr.&#39;s anti-Semitism</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/">Delivery apps just did the impossible.</a></li> <b>Culture Break</b><br><br><b>读。</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/mozart-in-motion-his-work-and-his-world-in-pieces-patrick-mackie/9780374606206?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Mozart in Motion</i></a> , by the British poet Patrick Mackie, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/mozart-in-motion-book-review-music/674726/">explores the secret to Mozart&#39;s lasting appeal</a> .<br><br> <b>Watch.</b> Beneath the hijinks and lewdness, the show <i>Dave</i> (streaming on Hulu) constructs <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/">an unlikely model</a> for male friendship.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">Play our daily crossword.</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>I like to bake, and find doing so relaxing. But in the summer, when my apartment is hot, I turn to treats that don&#39;t require baking. (In case it hasn&#39;t become clear: I do not enjoy the sensation of being overheated.) One very easy and fun one I have returned to is these <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018460-chocolate-peanut-butter-cups">chocolate-peanut-butter cups</a> , courtesy of Samantha Seneviratne. I don&#39;t have a double boiler or a microwave, so I boil water in a saucepan and melt chocolate chips in a metal bowl on top of it. And I like cashew butter, so I use that instead of peanut butter. The effort-to-reward ratio is high: These take just a few minutes of active work and render delightful little treats.<br><br> — Lora<br><br> <i>Katherine Hu contributed to this newsletter.</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Businessmen Broke Hollywood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>现在他们不想支付员工工资。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0uua5U8CtPMn05n96loBLb7ojPs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/hollywood_strike/original.jpg" alt="好莱坞演员罢工的照片。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大卫·布托 / Redux</figcaption></figure>好莱坞机器——从剧本写作、拍摄和制作，到深夜脱口秀公关——已经正式停止运转。<br><br>周四， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">演员们举行罢工。</a>在无所畏惧的情景喜剧保姆弗兰·德雷舍 (Fran Drescher) 的领导下，SAG-AFTRA 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">16 万名成员</a>在与制片厂的谈判破裂后停止了工作。他们加入了美国作家协会的行列，该协会的成员（包括我本人）自五月以来一直在罢工。<br><br>自 1960 年以来，我们两个工会就没有一起罢工过。拍摄地点的编剧纠察队已经关闭了估计 80% 的制作。现在，美国演员工会的罢工规则规定，演员不仅不能为作品拍摄或做配音工作，而且还不能为作品拍摄或配音。他们也不能参加红地毯或宣传任何电影协会的项目——这已经是一个挑战，因为编剧罢工已经关闭了作为新闻界主要内容的夜间脱口秀节目。<br><br>就像编剧一样，演员们也在寻求增加剩余报酬——类似于版税支票的补偿——曾经可靠的收入在转向流媒体的过程中几乎消失了。演员们也在利用他们的声音和图像寻求针对人工智能的保护。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">霍奇特尔·冈萨雷斯：“一切都从我们开始”</a><br><br>迪士尼首席执行​​官鲍勃·艾格 (Bob Iger) 称这些期望“不现实”。他指责罢工者“增加了该行业已经面临的一系列挑战，坦率地说，这些挑战非常具有破坏性和危险性。”<br><br>就在几天前，一位工作室高管告诉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/writers-strike-hollywood-studios-deal-fight-wga-actors-1235434335/"><i>Deadline</i></a> ，他们的策略是“让事情拖延下去，直到工会成员开始失去他们的公寓和房子”。<br><br>驱逐是一种相当残酷的劳资谈判策略。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官们<i>正在</i>遭受苦难。主要不是来自劳资纠纷、行业混乱或公共关系问题，而是来自明显的无知，这似乎是所有行业高管的普遍现象。在向华尔街交付的压力下，太多的首席执行官失去了自己电影的情节。他们经营公司并不是为了盈利地提供优质产品，例如一本书或一杯咖啡，或者在这种情况下，是一部电影或电视节目。他们经营公司是为了创造丰厚的利润。他们的产品质量已经不再重要。<br><br>如果你对此表示怀疑，请考虑一下上周宣布艾美奖提名时，最大的份额流向了 HBO Max，这个享有盛誉的平台已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.insiderintelligence.com/content/charting-new-course-adapting-advertising-landscape-after-hbo-max-discovery-merger">不再以该名称存在</a>，因为华纳兄弟探索频道 (Warner Bros. Discovery) 接管了这个传统品牌的流媒体部门，并且把它折叠成一个杂乱的应用程序，里面挤满了低预算的真人秀节目。我们处于颠倒的状态。<br><br>作家和演员都陷入了流媒体的转向，其疯狂的逻辑<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/writers-guild-contract-negotiation-mini-room-1235568173/">颠覆了长期的工作实践</a>，慢慢开始用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/28/18637135/hollywood-ai-film-decision-script-analysis-data-machine-learning">人工智能</a>取代人类本能，并消除了工人的收入来源。<br><br>例如，演员马克·普罗克什 (Mark Proksch) 在<i>《办公室》</i>中客串一季的剩余收入中赚了更多钱，<i> </i>在旧体制下，比他在新体制下主演<i>《我们在阴影中做什么》</i>五季还要多<i>。</i><br><br>现在，正当好莱坞工作人员认为我们需要调整薪酬模式以适应流媒体时代时，制片厂却告诉我们，我们无法获得公平的报酬，因为流媒体模式已被打破。正是那些打破了这一规则的工作室高管——其中许多是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/ceo-pay-wga-writers-strike-1235351572/">千万富翁</a>——告诉了我们这一点。<br><br>这是最高管理层无知的另一个方面：疯狂的高管薪酬让领导者完全脱离了他们雇用的员工的生活。华纳兄弟和探索频道的首席执行官大卫·扎斯拉夫 (David Zaslav) 2021 年收入为 2.47 亿美元，这一事实让人很难接受他拒绝在每年导致中产阶级演员损失数千美元的问题上做出让步的事实。<br><br>你可以随心所欲地争论是否有人应该赚这么多钱，但这些领导者做出了一些灾难性的商业决策。<br><br>在大流行期间每个人都被困在家里的短暂时刻，转向流媒体是非常有利可图的。人们不能在音乐会、外出就餐或旅行上花钱，因此他们在流媒体服务上花费异常金额感到放心。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官看到了 Netflix 的成功，竞相复制一种模式，但不知道这种模式是否可持续，这种模式依赖于工会人才不断生产新的（且昂贵的）娱乐内容。他们对企业的看法是错误的，但更错误的是他们认为劳工会遵守规定。这个支点不是演员和编剧做出的，而是演员和编剧做出的。他们为什么要付出代价？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">阅读：为什么你应该关注好莱坞编剧的罢工</a><br><br>如果转向流媒体是一个错误，导致这些企业真的陷入困境——考虑到这些高管薪酬方案的规模，这种情况很难成立——我们也将不得不受苦。但如果我们在困难时期受苦，我们也应该在富裕时期分享利润。这就是谈判的目的。高管们能够纠正这艘船的唯一方法就是重新制作不容错过的节目，如果没有我们，他们将无法做到这一点。<br><br>由于缺乏优秀的剧本作家，好莱坞的高管们只能借鉴玛丽·安托瓦内特的台词。但革命者已经在外面拆除了宫殿。在伦敦，<i>奥本海默</i>的演员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oppenheimer-stars-walk-out-london-premiere-actors-strike-emily-blunt-matt-damon-florence-pugh-cillian-murphy/">走出了</a>电影的首映式。<i>芭比娃娃</i>的新闻发布会已停止；就连明星们粉红色的社交媒体账户也被黑了。艾美奖颁奖典礼可能会被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/21/business/media/emmy-awards-writers-strike.html">推迟</a>。动漫展将没有演员或作家。我非常希望电影公司能够早日认识到，即使这会暂时伤害股东，但从长远来看，好的娱乐永远是好生意。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 19:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Voicebot Just Left Me Speechless]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>生成式人工智能解决了困扰我的语音助手多年的问题。<br>说出我的名字 Saahil Desai 并不难。 Saahil：与<em>锯木厂</em>押韵，或者至少可以让你达到 90%。 Desai：就像<em>决定</em>把最后一点砍掉。确实如此。<br><br>然而，我的名字常常会被淹没在一大堆失态和错误中。最常见的一个，Sa <em>-heel</em> ，至少是一个诚实的尝试——不像它的突变双胞胎，一个单音节的混乱，听起来像<em>海豹。</em>其他人则违背了所有可能的逻辑。有一次，一位大学同学读到我的名字，停顿了一下，然后自信地说：“嗨，西雅图。”<br><br>但最让我烦恼的错误发音却不是任何人都能说出来的。它们来自机器人。一整天，Siri 都会通过塞在我耳朵里的 AirPods 读出我的短信，并将我的名字混入<em>Sahul</em>中。它比我用来转录采访的人工智能服务要好，后者通过一串似乎从失败的英国男孩乐队中剥离出来的名字（奈杰尔、萨尔、迈克尔、丹尼尔、斯科特·希尔）来识别我。硅谷渴望其产品能够改变世界，但显然这也意味着名称的改变<em>。</em><br><br>或者至少我是这么认为的。听听这个： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567406875&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/eleven-labs" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="十一个实验室">Eleven Labs</a>这是来自 ElevenLabs 的一个名为 Adam 的人工智能声音，ElevenLabs 是一家专门从事语音克隆的初创公司。 （这有点像音频中的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/09/ai-art-generators-future/671568/">DALL-E</a> 。）这个机器人不仅能很好地说出我的名字，而且还能很好地说出我的名字。它比我能更好地说出我的名字。毕竟，萨希尔来自梵语，而我不会说这种语言。最终的结果是一种熟悉的多巴胺的冲击，一种令人惊奇的感觉，就像在技术上找到一个刻有你名字的纪念品钥匙链一样。<br><br>除了可以写俳句的聊天机器人和可以按照毕加索风格绘制披萨的艺术机器人之外，生成式人工智能革命还催生了最终可以确定我的名字的语音机器人。正如 ChatGPT 从互联网帖子中学习到的那样，ElevenLabs 在大量音频片段上训练其声音，以了解如何像人们一样说话——至少<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">500,000 小时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">，而</a>早期语音模型需要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://research.facebook.com/file/649409006862002/paper_fixed.pdf">数十或数百</a>小时的音频。 “我们在过去两年里一直在开发一种新的语音基础模型，”ElevenLabs 首席执行官 Mati Staniszewski 在一封电子邮件中写道。 “这意味着我们的模型是上下文感知且与语言无关的，因此能够更好地捕捉名称等细微差别，并提供反映文本输入的语调和情感。”较新的语音机器人的数据可能包括任意数量的专门用于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.howtopronounce.com/">发音的</a>网站，如果有人在有声读物、播客或 YouTube 视频中正确说出了你的名字，较新的人工智能模型可能会记录下来。<br><br>亚马逊、谷歌、Meta 和微软等公司也在开发更先进的语音机器人——尽管它们仍然是鱼龙混杂。我在他们每个人的人工智能语音程序上测试了同一句话——“来吧，说 Saahil Desai 并不难”。他们都能应付德赛，但迎接我的却不是萨希尔完美发音的合唱。亚马逊的 Polly 软件可能比 Siri 更糟糕，它认为我的名字类似于 Saaaaal： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567407838&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/amazon-polly" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="亚马逊波莉">Amazon Polly</a>谷歌云和 Microsoft Azure 都无伤大雅，但并不完美，稍微将 Saahil 扭曲成一种明显陌生的东西。没有什么可以打败 ElevenLabs，但 Voicebox（Meta 尚未发布的工具）非常接近：该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.facebook.com/blog/voicebox-generative-ai-model-speech/">最近将其吹捧</a>为“语音生成人工智能的突破”： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567408888&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/meta-voicebox" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="元语音盒">Meta Voicebox</a>计算机现在可以说出比我自己的名字更多的名字。 “前几天，当我和我的学生在 CNN 的安德森·库珀 (Anderson Cooper) 的 ElevenLabs 上录制了一段录音时，我注意到了同样的事情，说‘哈尼·法里德教授是一个彻头彻尾的废物’（这是一个很长的故事），”汉尼·法里德 (Hany Farid) 说道。加州大学伯克利分校计算机科学家在一封电子邮件中写道。 “我很惊讶它能很好地发音我的名字。我还注意到它可以正确发音我的非美国学生的名字。”我测试过的其他棘手的名字也表现良好：ElevenLabs 确定了 Lupita Nyong&#39;o 和 Timothée Chalamet，尽管它把可怜的 Pete Buttigieg 的姓氏变成了非常不幸的 Buttygig。<br><br>人工智能声音现在可以说出不寻常的名字，这可不是一件小事。他们面临着同样的发音困难，这让许多人感到困惑。 names like Giannis Antetokounmpo don&#39;t abide by the rules of English, while even a simpler name can have multiple pronunciations (And <em>rea</em> or <em>And</em> rea?) or spellings (Michaela? Mikayla? Michela?). Farid 表示，如果 AI 声音的颜色和纹理听起来比人类的 HAL 9000 更高，那么这个名字可能仍然听起来平淡无奇。<br><br>前几代语音助手——Siri、Alexa、Google Assistant、汽车的 GPS——只是没有足够的信息来完成所有这些步骤。 （在某些情况下，你可以自己提供这些信息：Apple 的一位发言人告诉我，你可以在通讯录应用程序中手动输入姓名的拼音，以调整 Siri 的读取方式。）多年来，这项技术“确实处于停滞状态” ，”法里德写道。 “它真的很难穿过那个恐怖谷，它有点像人类，但也有点奇怪。然后它就直接冲破了门。”受人脑启发的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.15561.pdf">“深度学习”技术的</a>进步可以更容易地发现音高、节奏和语调的模式。<br><br>这就是人工智能目前的奇怪矛盾：尽管这项技术很容易产生偏见，从而疏远用户（语音助手比白人说话者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/applij/advance-article/doi/10.1093/applin/amac066/6901317">更容易错误地识别</a>黑人说话者的话语），但它也可以帮助消除冒泡的较小的疏远感。不断听到机器人错误地说出我的名字是一种数字侮辱，它提醒我，我的设备似乎不是为我而设计的，尽管 Saahil Desai 在印度是一个常见的名字。我的蓝色 iPhone 12 是一块六英寸厚的平板，它比我生命中的任何其他物品都更能容纳<em>我</em>。然而它仍然搞砸了我身份的最基本的事情。<br><br>但机器人能够理解并说出我和你的名字的世界也是一个令人毛骨悚然的世界。 ElevenLabs 所采用的声音克隆技术已被用来制作可信的深度伪造品——粗鲁的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-taylor-swift-fan-generated-deepfakes-misinformation/673596/">泰勒·斯威夫特</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/">乔·罗根和本·夏皮罗辩论</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/"><em>《料理鼠王》</em></a> 、艾玛·沃特森阅读<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs"><em>《我的奋斗》</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs">的一部分</a><em>。</em>当另一端的声音可以像你的亲戚一样说出你的名字时，冒充你认识的人的人工智能骗局就更加可信。<br><br>一旦我清楚地知道我无法击败 ElevenLabs，我就输入了我的中间名 Abhijit。出来的是一团乱七八糟的音节，我永远也骗不了。好吧，好吧：我承认说萨希尔·阿比吉特·德赛实际上很难。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 16:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/</item></channel></rss>